# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alba
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] An election for the Scottish Parliament was held on 6 May 2021 under the provisions of the Scotland Act 1998.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] It was the sixth Scottish Parliament election since the devolved parliament was established in 1999.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] 129 Members of the Scottish Parliament were elected.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election was held alongside the Senedd election in Wales, English local elections, London Assembly and mayoral election and the Hartlepool by-election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election campaign started on 25 March 2021, during the COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] As a result, Parliament went into recess on 5 May, the day before the election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Of those five parties, three had changed their leader since the 2016 election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Newer parties set up since the 2016 election included: Reform UK Scotland, led by Michelle Ballantyne; the Alba Party, led by former First Minister and SNP leader Alex Salmond; and All for Unity, led by George Galloway.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] These parties only competed for seats on the regional lists.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election resulted in the SNP winning a fourth consecutive term in government.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] They won 64 seats, a net increase of one from the 2016 election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP gained Edinburgh Central, Ayr, and East Lothian, as well as winning the largest share of the popular vote and the largest number of constituency seats in any Scottish Parliament election (62).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Greens won eight seats, their best result to date at a Scottish Parliament election, while the Conservatives retained second place with 31 seats.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Labour had its worst-ever result with 22 seats, and the lowest share of the vote in both constituency and list votes for either Westminster or Holyrood since 1910.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats also had their worst showing at a Holyrood election to date, winning only four seats.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP and the Greens, both of which support Scottish independence, won 72 of the 129 seats in the parliament.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Unionist parties (that is, those against independence) achieved a small majority of votes in constituency contests, whilst pro-independence parties achieved a small majority in the regional lists.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The turnout was 63.5%, which is the highest ever at a Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Following the election, the third Sturgeon government was formed.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] It initially consisted of just the SNP, but later included Slater and Harvie of the Scottish Greens as junior ministers after the two parties negotiated a power-sharing agreement.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] At the 2016 election, the ruling Scottish National Party (SNP) lost its parliamentary majority but was able to continue governing under Nicola Sturgeon as a minority administration.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] At the same election, the Conservatives overtook Labour to place second, whilst the Greens overtook the Liberal Democrats to place fourth.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] No representatives of minor parties were elected to the Parliament.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Three parties had undergone leadership changes since the 2016 election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In August 2017, Kezia Dugdale resigned as leader of Scottish Labour and was replaced by Richard Leonard.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In January 2021, less than four months before the election, Leonard resigned.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Anas Sarwar won the subsequent leadership election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In August 2019, Lorna Slater and Patrick Harvie became co-leaders of the Scottish Greens.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Also in August 2019, Ruth Davidson resigned as leader of the Scottish Conservatives and was succeeded by Jackson Carlaw.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Carlaw resigned as leader in July 2020, with Douglas Ross winning the subsequent leadership election unopposed.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The 2021 election was the first to come after the passage of the Scottish Elections (Franchise and Representation) Act, which extended the franchise to those serving prison sentences of 12 months or less.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In 2005, the United Kingdom was found in breach of Protocol 1, Article 3 of the European Convention on Human Rights in regards to prisoner voting rights in the European Court of Human Rights as a result of *Hirst v United Kingdom (No 2)*; the Act brings Scotland in line with the court ruling.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This act also allows all foreign nationals resident in Scotland to vote and all those with indefinite leave to remain or equivalent status, including pre–settled status in the United Kingdom, to stand as candidates.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A BBC News report in April 2021 said that there were around 55,000 foreign nationals who had been given the right to vote as a result of these changes, including 20,000 refugees.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Under the Scotland Act 1998, an ordinary general election to the Scottish Parliament would normally have been held on the first Thursday in May four years after the 2016 election, i.e. in May 2020.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This would have clashed with the proposed date of a UK general election, although this became a moot point when a snap UK general election was held in June 2017 (a further UK general election was held in December 2019).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In November 2015, the Scottish Government published a Scottish Elections (Dates) Bill, which proposed to extend the term of the Parliament to five years.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 25 February 2016 and received Royal Assent on 30 March 2016, setting the new date for the election as 6 May 2021.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Nevertheless, no extraordinary general elections have been held to date.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Any extraordinary general election would be in addition to the ordinary general elections, unless held less than six months before the due date of an ordinary general election, in which case it would supplant it.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This would not affect the year in which the subsequent ordinary general election would be held.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 16 November 2020, the Scottish General Election (Coronavirus) Bill was introduced.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This draft legislation stated that while the next election was intended to be held on 6 May 2021, the Presiding Officer would gain the power to postpone the election by up to six months if the spread of COVID-19 made that date impractical.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The bill also proposed to change the date of dissolution to the day before the election, meaning that the Parliament could be recalled during the election period.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The bill was enacted and received Royal Assent on 29 January 2021.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Parliament was in fact recalled on 12 April, to allow MSPs to mark the death of Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] James Dornan announced in February 2020 his intention to retire at the next Holyrood election, but reversed this decision some months later.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP, Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats fielded candidates in all 73 constituencies and all eight of the regional ballots.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Five other parties contested both all eight regions and at least one constituency: the Scottish Greens (12 constituencies) the Scottish Libertarian Party (9), the Scottish Family Party (7), UKIP (5) and the Freedom Alliance (4).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Four parties – Abolish the Scottish Parliament Party, Alba Party, All for Unity, and Reform UK – stood in all eight electoral regions, but did not contest any constituencies.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Five other parties – Independent Green Voice (5 regions), Renew (5), the Social Democratic Party (2), Women's Equality (2) and Animal Welfare (1) – contested some of the regions, but not any constituencies.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Socialist Party, which participated in the last election as part of the electoral alliance RISE – Scotland's Left Alliance, opted not to participate in this election, for the first time since its inception.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The total number of Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) elected to the Parliament was 129.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Parliament uses an additional member system (AMS), designed to produce approximate proportional representation for each region.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] There are 8 regions, each sub-divided into 8 to 10 single-member constituencies.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Each constituency elects one MSP by the plurality (first past the post) system of election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Each region elects 7 additional MSPs using an additional member system.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A modified D'Hondt method using the constituency results is used to elect these additional MSPs.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The boundaries of the 73 constituencies last changed as of the 2011 Scottish Parliament election, as did the configuration of the electoral regions used to elect "list" members of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] These revisions were the outcome of the First Periodical Review of the Scottish Parliament's constituencies and regions conducted by the Boundary Commission for Scotland; the Review was announced on 3 July 2007 and the Commission published its final report on 26 May 2010.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The size difference between Westminster and Holyrood boundaries was due to diverge further upon the implementation of the Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies, which has not been voted upon by Parliament.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The 2023 Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies for a UK total of 650 MPs commenced in England in 2021 and will complete for the UK by 2023.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The election campaign started on 25 March 2021.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Scottish Conservatives launched their campaign the same day, with a focus on promoting Scotland's recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 26 March 2021, the Alba Party was publicly launched by former First Minister of Scotland and SNP leader, Alex Salmond.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The party announced plans to stand list-only candidates.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Two sitting SNP MPs later defected to the Alba party.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Action for Independence party, which had intended to pursue a similar list-only strategy, announced they would stand down their candidates in favour of Alba.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Sturgeon said she would refuse to have any dealings with Salmond unless he apologises to the women who had accused him of harassment.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Salmond was ultimately acquitted of all charges.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] BBC Scotland announced that it would broadcast two debates between the main parties' leaders; the first was aired on 30 March 2021 and was moderated by the corporation's Scotland editor Sarah Smith.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The debate included key questions from the audience on the COVID-19 recovery, climate change, and a second referendum on Scottish independence.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The second BBC debate was held on 4 May 2021 and was moderated by BBC Scotland's political editor Glenn Campbell.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Commercial broadcaster STV held their leaders' debate on 13 April, moderated by their political editor Colin Mackay.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] NUS Scotland held a debate, specifically on student issues, on 20 April; it was moderated by NUS Scotland president Matt Crilly and featured the three main party leaders.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 1 April, Planet Radio announced that their Clyde 2 station would be hosting a Leaders Phone-In with the main party leaders every Sunday before the election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Douglas Ross was the first to be interviewed on 4 April, with Willie Rennie following on 18 April.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Whilst Nicola Sturgeon was set to be interviewed on 11 April, campaigning was delayed following the death of Prince Philip and her phone-in was instead held on 22 April.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Patrick Harvie followed on 25 April; and Anas Sarwar had the final phone-in on 2 May.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Following Prince Philip's death on 9 April, the SNP, Conservatives, Labour, Greens and Liberal Democrats said they would suspend election campaigning until further notice.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] After discussion between the parties, they agreed to resume campaigning after a special parliamentary session on 12 April to make tributes and to pause activities again on the day of the funeral (17 April).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Graph of opinion poll results prior to the 2021 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Below are listed all the constituencies which required a swing of less than 5% from the 2016 result to change hands.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The most marginal opportunity for the Greens was in Glasgow Kelvin, which they needed a 7.1% swing to gain.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats' best bet was Caithness, Sutherland and Ross, which required a 6.1% swing.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP ended up holding both of these constituencies.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] (Note: no mechanism is used to have the overall seat counts for each party reflect the party share of the overall vote.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The SNP won 64 seats, falling one seat short of an overall majority.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Some commentators put this down to unionists voting tactically for Conservative, Labour and Liberal Democrat candidates.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] In *The National*, Emer O'Toole questioned whether social media adverts with "a lack of transparency over funding" may have cost the SNP key seats as well.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The day before the election, *The Guardian* reported that anti-independence groups and campaigners had "spent tens of thousands of pounds in the past week", including on Facebook adverts, calling for tactical voting to prevent the SNP getting a majority.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Additionally, the Greens claimed that they may have been deprived of two seats because of Independent Green Voice (IGV), a far-right party which has nothing to do with the Scottish Greens (who support Scottish independence).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] IGV received nearly 10,000 votes, including 2,210 in Glasgow (where the Greens were 1,000 short of gaining a seat) and 1,690 in South Scotland (where the Greens fell 100 short).
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] This potentially prevented pro-independence parties from having a 19-seat majority instead of 15 seats.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The *Scottish and Welsh Election Studies 2021*, revealed on 13 June, found that around a third of Scottish voters who decided to vote differently in the run-up to the election did so to stop another party, and that 90% of those who did this did so in a bid to prevent the SNP winning the seat.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Rob Johns, Professor in Politics at the University of Essex, said: "[W]e found a lot more switching than we had expected.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The polls had suggested that not much was changing and obviously the overall election result was almost eerily similar to 2016.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] That can mean that nobody has changed their mind or it can mean lots of people have changed their mind – but these have cancelled out as people have moved in opposing directions.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Nicola Sturgeon was nominated as First Minister by a vote held on 18 May 2021.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Her cabinet was approved by the parliament two days later and thus the Third Sturgeon government, a minority government, was formed.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 3 August 2021, it was reported that a co-operation agreement between the SNP and the Greens was "on the brink of being finalised" and could see Green MSPs take ministerial positions in government.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] On 19 August, the power-sharing agreement between the two parties was announced.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Under the terms of the agreement, the Greens have two MSPs appointed as junior ministers in the government who are invited to attend cabinet meetings when their portfolios are being discussed.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The Greens signed up to the bulk of the SNP's policies, but in areas of disagreement such as international relations and fee-paying schools the two parties are free to publicly disagree.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] The agreement states that the Greens support the government on votes of confidence and supply.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] A deal that would see Patrick Harvie and Lorna Slater made ministers was revealed on 26 August, subject to being voted upon by Green Party members.
[src:alba/2021-scottish-parliament-election] Two days later, members of both parties overwhelmingly voted in favour of the deal.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The **A7** is a major road, partly a trunk road, that connects Edinburgh in Central Scotland to Carlisle in North West England.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 meets the M6 motorway close to Carlisle, which connects to the English motorway network.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The northern terminus of the A7 is the junction at North Bridge with Princes Street in Edinburgh, also the northern terminus of the A1 and the southern terminus of the A900.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The road passes Cameron Toll, before meeting the Edinburgh City Bypass at the Sheriffhall Roundabout.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] South of the bypass, the A7 continues through Midlothian past Newtongrange and Gorebridge.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing from Midlothian into the Scottish Borders, the road bypasses Heriot then passes through Stow to reach Galashiels.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 becomes a trunk road at the southern boundary of Galashiels.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] It continues south to Selkirk; a bypass here has been proposed for years but not implemented.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] This section of the A7 runs parallel to the Borders Railway which opened in 2015; Network Rail and MPs met during construction to mitigate the effect of works traffic on the road.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] In Hawick the A7 continues along the north bank of the River Teviot to cross the river at the Albert Bridge and follows the south bank of the river towards Langholm, then bypasses Canonbie.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] South of Langholm the road has been improved, allowing for overtaking.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing across the English border, the A7 goes through Longtown, before meeting the A689 and the M6 at the Greymoorhill Roundabout.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 becomes a dual carriageway close to the Kingstown Industrial Estate on the northern fringe of Carlisle.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] Continuing as a single carriageway road, the A7 crosses the River Eden over Eden Bridge.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] At Hardwicke Circus Roundabout in the centre of Carlisle, the A7 meets the A595 to the west and southern Cumbria, then continues to form part of Carlisle's one way system through the city centre, meeting the A69 and finally becoming the A6 near Carlisle railway station.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The English section was detrunked in 2005.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] In the late 1970s, the A7 was described as being slow and tortuous.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] It was the 28th most dangerous UK road in 2017.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] The A7 Action Group was founded in 1990, and continues to lobby for safety improvements to the road, including a bypass of Selkirk.
[src:alba/a7-road-great-britain] Note: Junctions are listed northbound from Carlisle to Edinburgh.
[src:alba/alba-county] "Alba", meaning "white" in Latin and Romanian, is derived from the name of the city of Alba Iulia.
[src:alba/alba-county] In Hungarian, the county is known as *Fehér megye* (fehér also meaning white), and in German as *Kreis Karlsburg*.
[src:alba/alba-county] This county has a total area of 6,242 km2 (2,410 sq mi), with mountains occupying about 59% of its surface.
[src:alba/alba-county] The Apuseni Mountains are in the northwest; the northeastern side of the Parâng Mountains group – the Șureanu and Cindrel mountains – are in the south.
[src:alba/alba-county] In the east there is the Transylvanian Plateau with deep but wide valleys.
[src:alba/alba-county] The three main elements are separated by the Mureș River valley.
[src:alba/alba-county] The main rivers are the Mureș River and its tributaries, the Târnava, the Sebeș, and the Arieș.
[src:alba/alba-county] The mineral resources exploited in Alba county are metals (gold, silver, copper), salt, and construction materials, including marble and granite.
[src:alba/alba-county] According to the 2021 census, the county had a population of 325,941 and the population density was 52.2/km2 (135.2/sq mi).
[src:alba/alba-county] Alba County has 4 municipalities, 7 towns, and 67 communes.
[src:alba/alba-county] Historically, Alba de Jos County was located in the central-western part of Greater Romania, in the southwestern part of Transylvania, with a territory identical with the old Alsó-Fehér County of Hungary.
[src:alba/alba-county] After the administrative unification law in 1925, the name of the county changed to Alba County and the territory was reorganized.
[src:alba/alba-county] It was bordered on the west by Hunedoara County, to the north by Turda County, and to the east by the counties of Sibiu and Târnava-Mică.
[src:alba/alba-county] Its territory included the central part of the current Alba County.
[src:alba/alba-county] There were four towns: Alba Iulia, Abrud, Aiud, and Sebeș.
[src:alba/alba-county] According to the census data of 1930, the county's population was 212,749, of which 81.5% were Romanians, 11.3% Hungarians, 3.6% Germans, 1.8% Romanies, 1.4% Jews, as well as other minorities.
[src:alba/alba-county] In the religious aspect, the population consisted of 50.1% Eastern Orthodox, 31.6% Greek Catholics, 7.5% Reformed (Calvinists), 3.4% Roman Catholics, 3.3% Evangelical (Lutherans), 1.2% Unitarians, and other minorities.
[src:alba/alba-county] In 1930, the urban population of the county was 33,365, of which 58.8% were Romanians, 23.0% Hungarians, 8.2% Germans, 6.2% Jews, 1.6% Romanies, as well as other minorities.
[src:alba/alba-county] From the religious point of view, the urban population was made up of 38.3% Eastern Orthodox, 21.4% Greek Catholic, 14.7% Reformed (Calvinist), 7.2% Evangelical (Lutheran), 6.5% Jewish, as well as other minorities.
[src:alba/alba-county] After the 1938 Administrative and Constitutional Reform, this county merged with the counties of Ciuc, Odorhei, Sibiu, Târnava Mare, and Târnava Mică to form Ținutul Mureș.
[src:alba/alba-county] The county was re-established in 1940, but dissolved again in 1950.
[src:alba/alba-county] It was re-established in 1968 in its current borders.
[src:alba/alba-gu-bràth] The phrase is parallel to the Irish *Éirinn go Brách* ('Ireland Forever'), Welsh language slogan *Cymru am byth* ('Wales forever'), the Breton *Breizh da viken* ('Brittany forever') or the Cornish language *Kernow bys vykken* ('Cornwall forever').
[src:alba/alba-gu-bràth] In the 1995 film *Braveheart*, Scottish knight William Wallace (portrayed by Mel Gibson) shouts "Alba gu bràth" as he gallops across the front of his assembled Scottish troops just prior to their decisive victory at the Battle of Stirling Bridge.
[src:alba/alba-gu-bràth] In 2019 the Alba Gu Bràth tartan was added to the Scottish Register of Tartans.
[src:alba/alba-gu-bràth] For the 2024-2025 season, the Scottish Rugby team wore a white & sky blue away jersey] with "Alba gu bràth" written on the cuffs.
[src:alba/alba-gu-bràth] It has also been used on some Scotland Football National team shirts over the past few seasons.
[src:alba/alba-party] The **Alba Party** (Scottish Gaelic: *Pàrtaidh Alba*; lit.
[src:alba/alba-party] 'Scotland Party') was a Scottish nationalist and pro-independence political party in Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] Founded in February 2021, it was led by former first minister of Scotland and SNP leader Alex Salmond until his death in 2024.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond launched the party's 2021 Scottish Parliament election campaign in March 2021, with the party standing only region (list) candidates, but no constituency candidates.
[src:alba/alba-party] Two members of Parliament (MPs) in the UK House of Commons, Kenny MacAskill and Neale Hanvey, defected from the Scottish National Party (SNP) to the Alba Party on 27 March 2021, and a member of the Scottish Parliament, Ash Regan, defected on 28 October 2023, resigning from it in 2025.
[src:alba/alba-party] Several former SNP MPs also joined the Alba Party.
[src:alba/alba-party] In the 2024 general election, the Alba Party stood candidates in 19 constituencies across Scotland but achieved just 11,784 votes and won no seats.
[src:alba/alba-party] All their candidates lost their deposits.
[src:alba/alba-party] After Salmond's death, MacAskill won the 2025 Alba Party leadership election.
[src:alba/alba-party] In the lead-up to the 2026 Scottish Parliament election, the party suffered a financial crisis and MacAskill announced the party would likely be unable to stand.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 26 March 2026, Alba deregistered and dissolved as a party.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alex Salmond served as leader of the Scottish National Party (SNP) from 1990 to 2000 and again from 2004 to 2014, and as First Minister of Scotland from 2007 to 2014.
[src:alba/alba-party] He was succeeded in both positions in 2014 by his former deputy, Nicola Sturgeon.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond resigned from the SNP in 2018 following accusations of sexual misconduct, which he denied.
[src:alba/alba-party] He was acquitted of charges made against him in a subsequent court case in March 2020.
[src:alba/alba-party] Later that year, the possibility of Salmond leading a new party supporting Scottish independence was discussed, in the context of a feud between Sturgeon and Salmond, who accused Sturgeon's "inner circle" of plotting against him.
[src:alba/alba-party] Polling conducted in July 2020 reported that 40% of those who voted SNP at the 2019 general election would back a new independence-supporting party if it was led by Salmond.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party was founded and registered with the Electoral Commission by the retired television producer Laurie Flynn on 8 February 2021.
[src:alba/alba-party] *Alba* (pronounced [ˈal̪ˠapə] in Scottish Gaelic and Scottish English, /ˈælbə/ in British English) is the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 26 March 2021, Salmond announced at the party's election launch that he had joined the party and would become the new leader, taking over from Flynn, after "discussions with Laurie and others from other list parties" over the prior weeks.
[src:alba/alba-party] During the announcement of candidates, it gained its first elected member, councillor Chris McEleny, who previously had served as the SNP group leader on Inverclyde Council and was due to be an SNP candidate for the 2021 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] The MPs Kenny MacAskill and Neale Hanvey, as well as the former MP Corri Wilson, joined the party on 26 March.
[src:alba/alba-party] The SNP's national equalities convener, Lynne Anderson, also defected to Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] BBC Scotland's political editor Glenn Campbell said the list of defectors to the party included "those who fear that gender self-identification for trans people poses a threat to women's rights" as well as politicians who personally support Salmond and his approach to Scottish independence.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party announced plans to stand at least four candidates for the list vote in every region in the 2021 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] Caroline McAllister, the SNP's women's convener and deputy leader of West Dunbartonshire council, joined the party and was announced as a candidate in the West Scotland region.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party endorsed voting for the SNP in the constituency vote while voting for the Alba Party for the list vote, to ensure more pro-independence MSPs are elected.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 26 March 2021, the Leader of Action for Independence, former SNP MSP Dave Thompson, stated that the party would be standing down all their candidates to support Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] Tommy Sheridan who had been seeking election as part of Action for Independence, joined the Alba Party on 28 March.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 29 March, former professional boxer Alex Arthur was announced as a list candidate, whilst former SNP MPs George Kerevan and Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh and former MSP Jim Eadie joined later that day.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party failed to win any seats in the election, after attracting only 1.7% of the vote.
[src:alba/alba-party] It received 44,000 votes, which was enough proportionally to win two or three seats, but its support was spread across multiple regions, with no concentration large enough to produce a seat.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond said that the party's results were "creditable" given its recent founding.
[src:alba/alba-party] According to Neville Kirk, some observers attributed Alba's poor performance to Salmond being "out of touch with the younger, greener and feminist activists attracted in large numbers to the independence cause", and to his "seemingly unapologetic behaviour towards his female staff complainants".
[src:alba/alba-party] Some commentators also argued that Alba had benefitted Sturgeon individually by removing some of her most vocal internal party critics from the political scene.
[src:alba/alba-party] A few months after the election, on 28 June 2021, the Electoral Commission rejected all seven of Alba's official descriptions.
[src:alba/alba-party] In a round-up of recent decisions, the Commission said all seven proposed ballot paper slogans failed to "meet the requirements of a description".
[src:alba/alba-party] Sturgeon and the SNP criticised the new party, questioning Salmond's fitness to take public office given the sexual harassment claims against him.
[src:alba/alba-party] Sturgeon said she would refuse to have any dealings with Salmond unless he apologised to the women who had accused him of harassment.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alex Salmond refused to apologise during his titular sexual harassment scandal and was found not guilty of 12 charges, and not proven of one.
[src:alba/alba-party] Lorna Slater, co-leader of the Scottish Greens, also criticised the new party, describing it as "a party thrown together", Neil Mackay called the party "Trumpian" and "a hotchpotch of social conservatives and nationalist fundamentalists".
[src:alba/alba-party] The party was further criticised as "cynical" for potentially using women's rights as a campaign issue despite making misleading statements about one of their candidates' role in Glasgow City Council's equal pay dispute.
[src:alba/alba-party] In April 2021, Margaret Lynch claimed that the SNP's Scottish Government was funding LGBT rights groups that wanted to lower the age of consent to 10 years old.
[src:alba/alba-party] The SNP described this as "untrue" and Lynch was later criticised by Scottish Greens co-leader Patrick Harvie.
[src:alba/alba-party] *The Scotsman* repeated her claim that LGBT organisations which received "£2.8 million of Scottish public funds" have signed a letter advocating lowering the age of consent to 10 years of age.
[src:alba/alba-party] LGBT charity Stonewall called on Lynch to retract the allegation about their organisation and apologise.
[src:alba/alba-party] ILGA World released the statement that the claims are dangerous and irresponsible, that they urge those making or sharing them, to stop".
[src:alba/alba-party] LGBT Youth Scotland described Lynch's claims as "vicious lies" and "an act of prejudice and discrimination that repeats harmful myths".
[src:alba/alba-party] When asked by *The Scotsman* whether Lynch's position was also that of the party, Alba refused to comment.
[src:alba/alba-party] Former SNP councillor Austin Sheridan left the Alba Party, describing Lynch's comments stating there was "no way I can be part of a party that tolerates such views.
[src:alba/alba-party] In an article in *The Times*, Lynch claimed that trans rights would allow access by "sexual predators".
[src:alba/alba-party] However, Alba as a party had not condemned the claim made by Lynch, members citing the Isla Bryson case during the Gender Recognition Reform (Scotland) Bill push through where Bryson, a trans woman, was jailed within a women-only prison for sexually assaulting two women before transitioning.
[src:alba/alba-party] Bryson was later relocated to a male-only prison, receiving eight years in jail.
[src:alba/alba-party] For the 2022 Scottish local elections, the Alba Party announced that 111 candidates would be standing in councils across Scotland to win as many as possible.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond launched the party's manifesto at the Caird Hall in Dundee with the main aim of electing the first councillors under the Alba banner.
[src:alba/alba-party] Ahead of the election, Salmond said that he was confident that the party would win seats.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party failed to win any seats at the election, attracting 0.7% of first preference votes.
[src:alba/alba-party] All of the councillors who defected to the party from the SNP failed to be elected, including Christopher McEleny, the party's General Secretary, who only received 126 votes.
[src:alba/alba-party] In response to the result, Salmond expressed his disappointment with the outcome and said that it would take time for the party to build enough support to have candidates elected.
[src:alba/alba-party] The week after the elections, Kamran Butt, who, although not elected, was the most successful Alba candidate, defected to the SNP.
[src:alba/alba-party] He claimed that joining the SNP was the only way that independence and strong governance could be delivered in Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] The same day, Salmond stated that all pro-independence parties needed to work together if Scottish independence was to be achieved.
[src:alba/alba-party] He said that the proposed 2023 independence referendum would need to take place, but if it didn't then there would be huge political change in Scotland in which Alba would play a strong part.
[src:alba/alba-party] In December 2022, polling suggested that Alba could win seats at the next Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] 34% of voters who backed the SNP in the 2021 Scottish Parliament constituency vote said they would vote for Alba with their regional list ballot to return a greater number of pro-independence MSPs, with 19% support overall.
[src:alba/alba-party] In late August 2023, Alba announced they would not contest the October Rutherglen and Hamilton West by-election, called after former SNP MP Margaret Ferrier was suspended from the House of Commons and recalled from her seat for breaching COVID-19 regulations.
[src:alba/alba-party] They accused the SNP of rebuffing their call for only one pro-independence candidate and said that this would allow the SNP to "fly solo" in the ballot.
[src:alba/alba-party] The seat was lost to Labour, who won an outright majority.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 28 October 2023, former leadership candidate Ash Regan defected to Alba, becoming the party's first member of the Scottish parliament and the party leader in the Scottish Parliament.
[src:alba/alba-party] The same month the "Scotland United" technical group was formed in the House of Commons between Alba and independent MP Angus MacNeil.
[src:alba/alba-party] In 2024, Alba started a campaign in favour of keeping the Grangemouth Refinery open.
[src:alba/alba-party] In March 2024, Eva Comrie, the party's equalities convener, who was also a founding member of the party, resigned from Alba, citing comments made by the party's women's convener, Yvonne Ridley, that trans-women are "assigned male at birth" as the reason.
[src:alba/alba-party] As a result, Salmond announced that Ridley was stepping down from the role.
[src:alba/alba-party] In November 2023, Salmond confirmed that the Alba Party would field candidates at the 2024 United Kingdom general election.
[src:alba/alba-party] In total, 19 candidates stood, including their sitting MPs: Kenny MacAskill and Neale Hanvey.
[src:alba/alba-party] At a press conference prior to candidate nominations closing, Salmond confirmed that he was not among the Alba candidates to be seeking election, instead telling journalists that it was his intention to contest the Banffshire and Buchan Coast seat at the next Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] The Proclaimers endorsed the party's campaign to save the Grangemouth Oil Refinery in the election.
[src:alba/alba-party] In the election, Alba received 11,784 votes (0.5%), and were unsuccessful in returning any MPs.
[src:alba/alba-party] Additionally, none of the candidates were successful in retaining their £500 election deposit, having failed to reach the 5% threshold required to do so.
[src:alba/alba-party] Their best result came in Cowdenbeath and Kirkcaldy, where Hanvey took 2.8% of the vote.
[src:alba/alba-party] MacAskill received 638 votes (1.5%) in Alloa and Grangemouth, coming behind Eva Comrie who ran as an independent.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba did not put up candidates in the North East of Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] As a result, Salmond admitted that he had voted SNP in his home constituency of Aberdeenshire North and Moray East.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 12 October 2024, Salmond died suddenly of a heart attack at the age of 69, whilst attending an event in North Macedonia.
[src:alba/alba-party] Under the party's constitution, the deputy leader would become acting leader whenever the role is vacant, holding office until a leadership election could be held.
[src:alba/alba-party] As a result, Kenny MacAskill became the interim leader.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 9 January 2025, Ash Regan announced that she would be running in the leadership election to succeed Salmond.
[src:alba/alba-party] In addition to the election of a new leader, the party also had a contest for the role of deputy leader, which saw Chris McEleny and Neale Hanvey stand for the position.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 26 March 2025, MacAskill was announced as the next leader of Alba, securing 52.3% of the vote to Regan's 47.7%.
[src:alba/alba-party] Hanvey won the deputy leadership election.
[src:alba/alba-party] In April 2025, MacAskill announced that Alba would once again field list-only candidates at the 2026 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba chose not to field a candidate for the 2025 Hamilton, Larkhall and Stonehouse by-election, which was held due to the death of the SNP's Christina McKelvie.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party said that their decision not to stand was as a mark of respect for McKelvie's work as an MSP, and to the wider independence movement.
[src:alba/alba-party] Additionally, Alba reiterated their intention to run on the regional lists in 2026.
[src:alba/alba-party] Ash Regan withdrew from the party in October 2025 to sit as an independent MSP, leaving the party with no representation in the Parliament.
[src:alba/alba-party] Later that month Hugh Kerr and Craig Murray left Alba to join Your Party.
[src:alba/alba-party] Kerr argued that Alba "was in its death throes” and "likely to die", while Murray argued that "the need for a real left-wing party is urgent".
[src:alba/alba-party] In response, MacAskill stated that he respected their decision to switch parties; he also stated that the Alba Party intended to treat the 2026 Scottish Parliament election as a "de facto referendum" on Scottish independence and campaign on economic issues.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 28 November, the party launched a petition to halt onshore wind farm development in Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] The petition argued that expansion of onshore wind farms is unnecessary and unwanted by local communities, and that the wind farms "damage our landscape, don’t bring energy prices down, and in many cases are simply used to make a quick buck by corporate fat cats".
[src:alba/alba-party] In December, it launched a similar campaign "It's Still Scotland's Oil", based on the SNP's "It's Scotland's Energy" campaign from the 1970s.
[src:alba/alba-party] The campaign protests the shutdown of Grangemouth refinery and Mossmorran plant, and argues for the importance of Scotland to develop its oil industry in order to create jobs and recreate the success of Norway's sovereign wealth fund.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 13 January 2026, Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh stepped down as the party's chair due to personal reasons, although she remained a member of the party's national executive committee.
[src:alba/alba-party] MacAskill wrote that he expected her to return to the post, and appointed Debbie Ewen as the interim chairwoman.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 1 February 2026, Tommy Sheridan was announced as Alba's front-running candidate in Glasgow at the upcoming Scottish Parliament election.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 21 February 2026, it was announced that Alba would be "unlikely" to contest the election due to financial irregularities with MacAskill informing members that the organisation was in a precarious financial position.
[src:alba/alba-party] Concerns were also raised about whether the party could continue to meet the Electoral Commission's regulatory requirements if its financial situation did not improve.
[src:alba/alba-party] The leadership's warning prompted internal backlash, with some figures arguing that any decision about the party's future should be taken collectively rather than by senior figures alone.
[src:alba/alba-party] Christina Hendry, niece of Alex Salmond, criticised the leadership's announcement and argued that any decision about the party's future should involve the wider membership.
[src:alba/alba-party] She expressed concern about suggestions that the party could stand down or de-register, stating that the independence movement should continue and urging members to remain engaged while discussions about Alba's next steps were ongoing.
[src:alba/alba-party] As of the announcement, no final decision had been confirmed, with the party's National Executive Committee expected to determine its next steps.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 23 February 2026, MacAskill said the party's financial crisis was linked to alleged fraud within its finances, which he stated amounted to "tens of thousands" of pounds.
[src:alba/alba-party] In media interviews, he said the situation had severely affected Alba's ability to campaign in the forthcoming election and confirmed that the matter had been reported to Police Scotland, while discussions with the Electoral Commission about the party's obligations were ongoing.
[src:alba/alba-party] The group announced plans to hold an emergency membership ballot on whether Alba should stand on the regional list and called on party headquarters to distribute voting instructions to all paid-up members.
[src:alba/alba-party] The faction argued that the party remained a "going concern" and cited disagreements over leadership authority, alongside reports that staff and activists had been blocked from accessing membership data.
[src:alba/alba-party] A whistleblower further alleged that party officials had restricted access to the membership database, intensifying the dispute over internal governance.
[src:alba/alba-party] Christina Hendry declined to back MacAskill as party leader, further highlighting divisions, while an Alba Party spokesperson stated that those seeking to assume control lacked a democratic mandate or constitutional authority to do so.
[src:alba/alba-party] In the letter, he also stated that there was no democratic or constitutional basis for other members to assume control of the party and that alleged attempts to interfere with party data controls had been reported to the Information Commissioner.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 28 February 2026, the Alba Continuation Group called on MacAskill to resign if he was not going to let Alba contest the election.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 1 March 2026, party officials publicly described Alba as "financially insolvent" and said it could not meet its existing debts, arguing that contesting the forthcoming election would expose NEC members to further financial liability.
[src:alba/alba-party] The statement followed renewed calls from more than fifty candidates and branch convenors for MacAskill and Hanvey to commit to standing in May or resign.
[src:alba/alba-party] A spokesperson said those seeking to assume control had not presented a viable financial plan.
[src:alba/alba-party] On the same day, an audio recording published by a political blog and attributed to director of operations Corri Wilson appeared to show her questioning the party’s electoral viability and referencing potential liabilities of around £200,000, further intensifying public scrutiny of the crisis.
[src:alba/alba-party] The group has also requested that dissenting NEC members be permitted to attend any meeting with the Electoral Commission, framing the dispute as one of constitutional authority and member governance.
[src:alba/alba-party] Within the first four hours of the launch of the fundraiser, the group raised £15,000 in four hours before reaching £28,000 a few hours afterwards.
[src:alba/alba-party] On 8 March 2026, MacAskill announced that the party would be wound down, citing a “dire financial plight”, declining membership and falling income.
[src:alba/alba-party] The decision was made after the party leadership met with the Electoral Commission, which advised that Alba was to either voluntarily deregister or face statutory deregistration.
[src:alba/alba-party] Addressing the Alba Continuation Group, MacAskill stated that the group was self-appointed and that Alba did not receive the money that the group had gathered; he added that any sums raised for the party would have to meet existing debts.
[src:alba/alba-party] The decision to de-register has effectively brought an end to the party, with MacNeil describing the development as a “sad and unnecessary end” to Salmond’s project while criticising the leadership’s handling of the situation.
[src:alba/alba-party] Following the announcement from MacAskill, several of Alba's candidates who were due to stand in the election, defected to Alliance to Liberate Scotland, including Sheridan and former Alba member, Craig Murray.
[src:alba/alba-party] Other Alba's candidates, such as Dhruva Kumar, also joined the Alliance to Liberate Scotland in order to continue their campaigns.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party officially deregistered and dissolved on 26 March 2026.
[src:alba/alba-party] The Alba Party supported Scottish nationalism, advocating Scottish independence as an "immediate necessity".
[src:alba/alba-party] Its stated goal was to build a "socially just and environmentally responsible" Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] After Queen Elizabeth II's death, the party called for Scotland to become a republic with "an elected head of state with similar powers to the *Uachtarán na hÉireann* (the President of Ireland)", with the final document of a written constitution for this purpose to be confirmed by a referendum.
[src:alba/alba-party] Its platform also opposed proposed changes to the Gender Recognition Act until a citizens' assembly can be formed to discuss and debate the perceived conflicts between sex- and gender-based rights.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alex Salmond described holding a gender-critical belief as a "cardinal aspect of ALBA policy".
[src:alba/alba-party] In March 2022, Salmond unveiled a 38-page "Wee Alba Book" which makes the "fundamental case for independence", covering issues such as Europe, currency and borders.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party officially described itself as left-of-centre, claiming to be more left-wing than the Scottish National Party.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond stated: "I had an idea a while back when leading another political party.
[src:alba/alba-party] I thought that if the SNP could present as a coherent left of centre political party it could replace the Labour Party as the dominant force in Scottish politics.
[src:alba/alba-party] As it was for the SNP and Labour so is it now for Alba and the SNP." Alba's politicians presented a variety of positions — Tommy Sheridan and George Kerevan were regarded as left-wing, along with Kenny MacAskill, who was also described as a social democrat.
[src:alba/alba-party] Ash Regan, the long-standing MP of Alba, was considered centre-right, but left the party in October 2025.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond himself was described as left-wing.
[src:alba/alba-party] Some political commentators, such as Gerry Hassan, were skeptical of the party's claim to be "more left-wing and working class" than the SNP.
[src:alba/alba-party] Europe Elects classified the party as centre-left.
[src:alba/alba-party] Nathalie Duclos of the University of Toulouse wrote that Alba was positioned on "the left or centre-left on the left-right axis", and Italian journal *Democrazia e Diritto* described it as "social-democratic left".
[src:alba/alba-party] It has also been described as the leftmost Scottish party along with the Greens, left of the SNP, and left-leaning.
[src:alba/alba-party] Economically, the party described itself as social democratic, and was also described as such by some observers, such as the Polish journalist Konrad Rękas, and *Democrazia e Diritto*.
[src:alba/alba-party] Two SNP Aberdeenshire councillors who defected to Alba in 2021, argued that they had done so because they "are committed to a social-democratic independent Scotland".
[src:alba/alba-party] The Common Weal Group, a SNP faction which promoted "genuine radical, anti-market policies", also defected to Alba, arguing that the party is building "a left-wing, progressive wing of the independence movement".
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba called for "a far bolder and more progressive tax system", "a social security system based on fairness", and an end to "the Westminster system of punishing those most in need in our society".
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba proposed a state house-building company that would build houses above the existing targets, and a Scottish state energy corporation that would produce energy using wave power and tidal power.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party stated that housebuilding should be state-owned as to clamp down on "speculative developers".
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba argued that Scotland should abandon pound sterling and the monetary union with the United Kingdom in favour of its own independent currency, arguing that Scotland "must have control over the money in its economy and how it’s managed".
[src:alba/alba-party] The party was protective of Scotland's oil industry and opposed proposals to phase it out, likening such attempts to Margaret Thatcher's shutdowns of British coal mines that led to the 1984–1985 United Kingdom miners' strike and disempowerment of the British trade union movement.
[src:alba/alba-party] In 2025, Alba launched a "It's Still Scotland's Oil" campaign inspired by SNP's 1970 "It's Scotland's Energy" one.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba argued that Scotland could recreate Norway's oil and gas policies that developed the Norwegian sovereign wealth fund worth over £1.5 trillion, and protested the shut down of Grangemouth refinery and Mossmorran plants.
[src:alba/alba-party] It called for "radical measures" to reduce energy prices, criticising the SNP for its "cautious incrementalism" on the economy.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba postulated a social energy tariff to offer lower prices to low-income households, and proposed using Scottish oil and gas revenues for industrial transition to renewable energy and state-owned housing, transport and retrofitting.
[src:alba/alba-party] Salmond described Alba as more radical than the SNP, with more left-wing economic policies: "It's true that we're also more radical [than SNP] in social and economic policy.
[src:alba/alba-party] Their proposals are good, but they're not enough.
[src:alba/alba-party] For example, the amount they want to allocate to each child to combat child poverty is ridiculous.
[src:alba/alba-party] We're proposing four times as much." According to Gregor Gall, a factor in the creation of Alba was the rightward shift of SNP's leadership towards accommodation with neoliberalism, which led to defection of left-wing SNP factions to Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] Tichys Einblick described the party as opposed to "SNP's woke side proposals", while Fraser Macmillan wrote that it offered an alternative to voters who oppose "SNP's social liberalism".
[src:alba/alba-party] Javier Castro Cruz stated that the party appealed to "pro-independence voters who are more socially conservative, a group that voted strongly for Brexit".
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba was officially opposed to further gender reforms proposed by the SNP, and spoke against liberalisation of gender recognition laws.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alex Salmond criticised the 2023 Gender Recognition Reform (Scotland) Bill as the "worst legislation in the history of devolution".
[src:alba/alba-party] He also argued that the gender legislation is meant to distract from socioeconomic issues, stating: "Clearly, that's the most important issue on your mind, with your coat on, at home, shivering on a Saturday afternoon in Bucksburn.
[src:alba/alba-party] Let's get back to the issues that matter to people!" Ash Regan cited this as a reason for joining Alba and called for an end to further legal action against the section 35 ruling by the UK Government.
[src:alba/alba-party] Canadian magazine L'Actualite described Alba as "more socially conservative" than the SNP, "particularly regarding LGBTQ+ issues".
[src:alba/alba-party] Journalist Helen Lewis argued that the party was ambiguous on social issues, on one hand comprising "older men for whom the new party is a refuge from wokeness", but including prominent lifelong feminists on the other.
[src:alba/alba-party] She noted that more than half of Alba's 2021 candidates were female.
[src:alba/alba-party] According to Caroline McAllister, a former SNP women's convener that defected to Alba, the party provided a safe "space where women can speak freely about their concerns about gender ideology".
[src:alba/alba-party] At the same time, she claimed that LGBT people, including transgender persons, were also welcome in the party.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba supported a future independent Scotland joining the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), arguing that it would mitigate the negative effects of Brexit while avoiding the "obligations and restrictions" of becoming an EU member.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party did not want Scotland to rejoin the European Union, although it was open to holding a referendum on the issue.
[src:alba/alba-party] It staunchly opposed NATO membership, and demanded the removal of the British nuclear arsenal and the nuclear submarine base HMNB Clyde at Faslane from Scotland.
[src:alba/alba-party] Regarding the Gaza war, the party expressed "solidarity with the Palestinian people" and called for an immediate ceasefire in Gaza.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba condemned the 2026 United States intervention in Venezuela, with the depute convenor of the party, Dhruva Kumar, describing it as the "older story" of "how US power behaves when oil and strategic resources are at stake".
[src:alba/alba-party] The party argued that US intervention in Venezuela represents a case in which "US sanctions have evolved into direct control over who can sell the country's oil" and "long-term management of another nation's core resource".
[src:alba/alba-party] According to Alba, President Donald Trump's plans to acquire Greenland also have the same goal.
[src:alba/alba-party] In the official party statement, MacAskill warned that US actions against Iran and Venezuela are part of a larger scheme to initiate a military conflict with China.
[src:alba/alba-party] Similarly, *The Political Quarterly* argued that the SNP and Alba correspond to the gradualist-fundamentalist split amongst Scottish nationalists, with the SNP representing gradualist nationalism and the Alba Party attempting to form a radically separatist, fundamentalist force.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba was described as "more populist" than SNP, and in 2021, 70% of its supporters wanted a Scottish independence referendum within 12 months, as opposed to 48% of SNP's supporters.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba postulated the unification of the Scottish national movement in order to recreate the 1980s Scottish Constitutional Convention that played a crucial role in the implementation of Scottish devolution.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party argued that the recreated convention would focus on Scottish independence.
[src:alba/alba-party] To this end, Alba become associated with the All Under One Banner movement composed of non-aligned Scottish nationalists.
[src:alba/alba-party] In 2023, Alba proposed an alliance with the SNP.
[src:alba/alba-party] In 2025, the party again proposed a convention of pro-independence parties, but the SNP and Scottish Greens reacted to the proposal with reluctance.
[src:alba/alba-party] The party never had any candidates directly elected.
[src:alba/alba-party] Their representatives, listed below, all defected having been elected as SNP candidates.
[src:alba/alba-party] Following Salmond's announcement, eleven councillors had joined the party by the end of March 2021.
[src:alba/alba-party] All eleven had been elected as SNP candidates, though three had already left that party.
[src:alba/alba-party] This included three councillors on Aberdeenshire Council and two on North Lanarkshire Council.
[src:alba/alba-party] Alba nominated 111 candidates for the 2022 Scottish local elections, including the 13 incumbent councillors who were elected as members of other parties before joining Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] In October 2023, Chris Cullen, a councillor in South Ayrshire Council defected from the SNP to Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] In March 2024, Karl Rosie became the party's second councillor when he also defected to Alba.
[src:alba/alba-party] He had been elected in Thurso and North West Caithness on The Highland Council and had left the SNP the previous month to sit as an independent.
[src:alba/alba-party] In December 2025 he resigned from Alba and became a member of the Highland Independents group.
[src:alba/alba] The term first appears in classical texts as Ἀλβίων **Albíōn** or Ἀλουΐων **Alouíōn** (in Ptolemy's writings in Greek), and later as **Albion** in Latin documents.
[src:alba/alba] Historically, the term refers to Britain as a whole and is ultimately based on the Indo-European root for "white".
[src:alba/alba] It later came to be used by Gaelic speakers in the form of **Alba** (dative **Albainn**, genitive **Albann**, now obsolete) as the name given to the former kingdom of the Picts which, when first used in this sense (around the time of king Causantín mac Áeda (Constantine II, 943–952)), had expanded.
[src:alba/alba] The region of Breadalbane (**Bràghad Albann**, the upper part of "Alba") takes its name from it as well.
[src:alba/alba] As time passed, that kingdom incorporated other territories to its south.
[src:alba/alba] It became re-Latinised in the High Medieval period as "Albania" (it is unclear whether it may ultimately share the same etymon as the modern Albania).
[src:alba/alba] This latter word was employed mainly by Celto-Latin writers, and most famously by Geoffrey of Monmouth.
[src:alba/alba] It was this word which passed into Middle English as Albany, although very rarely was this used for the Kingdom of Scotland, but rather for the notional Duchy of Albany.
[src:alba/alba] It is from the latter that Albany, the capital of the US state of New York, and Albany, Western Australia, take their names.
[src:alba/alba] BBC Alba, a television channel broadcasting mainly in Scottish Gaelic, was launched in September 2008 as a joint venture between the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) and Gaelic company MG Alba.
[src:alba/alba] A new version of Runrig's song *Alba* (originally on their album, *The Cutter and the Clan*) was featured on the channel's launch.
[src:alba/alba] In the mid-1990s, the Celtic League started a campaign to have the word "Alba" on the Scottish football and rugby tops.
[src:alba/alba] Since 2005, the SFA have supported the use of Scottish Gaelic by adding *Alba* on the back of the official team strip.
[src:alba/alba] However, as of 2008, the SRU is still being lobbied to have *Alba* added to the national rugby union strip.
[src:alba/alba] In 2007, the then Scottish Executive re-branded itself as "The Scottish Government" and started to use a bilingual logo with the Gaelic name *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:alba/alba] However, the Gaelic version from the outset had always been *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:alba/alba] The Scottish Parliament, likewise, uses the Gaelic name *Pàrlamaid na h-Alba*.
[src:alba/alba] A new welcome sign on the historic A7 route into Scotland was erected in 2009, with the text *Fàilte gu Alba*.
[src:alba/alba] Phrases such as *Alba gu bràth* may be used as a catch-phrase or rallying cry.
[src:alba/alba] It was used in the movie *Braveheart* as William Wallace encouraged the troops at the Battle of Stirling Bridge.
[src:alba/alba] In March 2021, former first minister of Scotland and leader of the SNP Alex Salmond launched the pro-independence Alba Party, set to contest the 2021 Scottish Parliament elections.
[src:alba/albanactus] Albanactus was stated to be the youngest of three sons of Brutus and Innogen, and a descendant of Aeneas of Troy.
[src:alba/albanactus] According to legend, upon their father's death, the eldest son Locrinus was given *Loegria*, Camber was given *Cambria* and Albanactus *Albania*.
[src:alba/albanactus] These names are merely reverse etymologies.
[src:alba/albanactus] Albanactus, for instance, is a reverse etymology of the Scottish word *Albannach* or "Alvannach" (Volcanic Highlands) [of Albanian Highland people called "Highlanders"] (Scotsman).
[src:alba/albanactus] Likewise, *Locrinus* represents the medieval Welsh word *Loegria* (England, except for Cornwall) (modern Welsh *Lloegr*), and Camber represents the Latin word Cambria or the Welsh word *Cymru* (Wales).
[src:alba/albanactus] It is recounted that Albanactus was killed shortly after he began his reign, by Humber, king of the Huns.
[src:alba/albanactus] Humber invaded Albany from Germany and met Albanactus's army in battle, where Humber killed Albanactus.
[src:alba/albanactus] This forced the people of Albany to flee south to Albanactus's brother, Locrinus.
[src:alba/albanactus] All this was supposedly before the Picts and Scots had invaded.
[src:alba/albanactus] Later Kings of England – particularly Edward I – used the Brutus and Albanactus legend as an excuse to claim superiority over and to conquer Scotland, arguing that as Locrinus was the oldest brother, so he and hence England had superior status.
[src:alba/albanactus] The same argument, of course, extended over Wales, as Camber was also junior to Locrinus.
[src:alba/albanactus] In Scottish origin myths, Albanactus had little place.
[src:alba/albanactus] The Scots instead stressed descent from Gaythelos (Gael) or Gaidel Glas and his wife Scota.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania was inhabited by several Illyrian tribes, among them the Ardiaei, Bylliones, Dassaretii, Enchele, and Taulantians, with the Chaonians settled in the southwest.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Several colonies were founded by the Ancient Greeks along the Albanian coast, most notably Apollonia.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Illyrians were the dominant power in Albania before the rise of Macedon.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Following the Illyrian Wars, Albania was integrated into the Roman Empire and remained in the Byzantine Empire after its partition.
[src:alba/albania-p01] During the Middle Ages, several Albanian principalities emerged, most notably the Principality of Arbanon, Kingdom of Albania, Principality of Albania and Albania Veneta.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In the 15th century, Albania became a center of resistance against Ottoman expansion under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, whose military campaigns repelled Ottoman advances for over two decades.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Although incorporated into the Ottoman Empire, Albania retained distinct cultural and social identities throughout four centuries of foreign rule, culminating in the Albanian Renaissance in the 19th century.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania declared independence in 1912, followed by a turbulent 20th century marked by monarchy, foreign occupation during both World Wars, and a communist regime under Enver Hoxha.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Since its independence in 1912, Albania has undergone a number of political changes, transitioning from a monarchy to a communist regime before becoming a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Governed by a constitution prioritising the separation of powers, the country's political structure includes a parliament, a ceremonial president, a functional prime minister and a hierarchy of courts.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania is a developing country with an upper-middle income economy driven by the service sector, with manufacturing and tourism, which attracted over 11 million visitors in 2024, also playing significant roles.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The illegal drug trade in Albania contributes around US$100 million to the economy per year.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After the dissolution of its communist system, the country shifted from centralised planning to an open market economy.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albanian citizens have universal health care access and free primary and secondary education.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The country is an official candidate for membership in the European Union, and has been negotiating accession since 2022.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The origin of the name "Albania" can be traced back to medieval Latin and the association with the Illyrian tribe of the Albani.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This connection is further supported by the writings of the Ancient Greek geographer Ptolemy during the 2nd century AD, where he included the settlement of Albanopolis situated to the northeast of Durrës.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The presence of a medieval settlement named Albanon or Arbanon hints at the possibility of historical continuity.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The precise relationship between these historical references and the question of whether Albanopolis was synonymous with Albanon remain subjects of scholarly debate.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Byzantine historian Michael Attaliates, in his 11th-century historical account, provides the earliest undisputed reference to the Albanians, when he mentions them as participants in a revolt against Constantinople in 1079.
[src:alba/albania-p01] He also identifies the Arbanitai as subjects of the Duke of Dyrrachium.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In the Middle Ages, Albania was denoted as *Arbëri* or *Arbëni* by its inhabitants, who identified themselves as *Arbëreshë* or *Arbëneshë*.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albanians employ the terms *Shqipëri* or *Shqipëria* for their nation, designations that trace their historical origins to the 14th century.
[src:alba/albania-p01] But only in the late 17th and early 18th centuries did these terms gradually supersede *Arbëria* and *Arbëreshë* among Albanians.
[src:alba/albania-p01] These two expressions are widely interpreted to symbolise "Children of the Eagles" and "Land of the Eagles".
[src:alba/albania-p01] Mesolithic habitation in Albania has been evidenced in several open-air sites which were close to the Adriatic coastline and in caves.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Mesolithic objects found in a cave near Xarrë include flint and jasper objects along with fossilised animal bones, while those discoveries at Mount Dajt comprise bone and stone tools similar to those of the Aurignacian culture.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Neolithic era in Albania began around 7000 BC and is evidenced in finds which indicate domestication of sheep and goats and small-scale agriculture.
[src:alba/albania-p01] A part of the Neolithic population may have been the same as the Mesolithic population of the southern Balkans, like in the Konispol cave, where the Mesolithic stratum co-exists with Pre-Pottery Neolithic finds.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Cardium pottery culture appears in coastal Albania and across the Adriatic after 6500 BC, while the settlements of the interior took part in the processes that formed the Starčevo culture.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Albanian bitumen mines of Selenicë provide early evidence of bitumen exploitation in Europe, dating to Late Neolithic Albania (from 5000 BC), when local communities used it as pigment for ceramic decoration, waterproofing, and adhesive for repairing broken vessels.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The bitumen of Selenicë circulated towards eastern Albania from the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] First evidence of its overseas trade export comes from the Neolithic and Bronze Age southern Italy.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The high-quality bitumen of Selenicë has been exploited throughout all the historical ages since the Late Neolithic era until today.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Indo-Europeanisation of Albania in the context of the IE-isation of the western Balkans began after 2800 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The presence of the Early Bronze Age tumuli in the vicinity of later Apollonia dates to 2679±174 calBC (2852–2505 calBC).
[src:alba/albania-p01] These burial mounds belong to the southern expression of the Adriatic-Ljubljana culture (related to the later Cetina culture), which moved southwards along the Adriatic from the northern Balkans.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The same community built similar mounds in Montenegro (Rakića Kuće) and northern Albania (Shtoj).
[src:alba/albania-p01] The first archaeogenetic find related to the IE-isation of Albania involves a man with predominantly Yamnaya ancestry buried in a tumulus of northeastern Albania, which dates to 2663–2472 calBC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age, Cetina culture sites and finds appear in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Cetina culture moved southwards across the Adriatic from the Cetina valley of Dalmatia.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The incorporated territory of Albania was historically inhabited by Indo-European peoples, amongst them numerous Illyrian and Epirote tribes.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The territory referred to as Illyria corresponded roughly to the area east of the Adriatic Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, extending in the south to the mouth of the Vjosë.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The first account of the Illyrian groups comes from the Periplus of the Euxine Sea, a Greek text written in the 4th century BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Bryges were also present in central Albania, while the south was inhabited by the Epirote Chaonians, whose capital was at Phoenice.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Other colonies, such as Apollonia and Epidamnos, were established by Greek city-states on the coast by the 7th century BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Illyrian Taulanti were a powerful Illyrian tribe among the earliest recorded tribes in the area.
[src:alba/albania-p01] They lived in an area that corresponds with much of present-day Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Together with the Dardanian ruler Cleitus, Glaucias, the ruler of the Taulantian kingdom, fought against Alexander the Great at the Battle of Pelium in 335 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] As time passed, the ruler of Ancient Macedonia, Cassander of Macedon, captured Apollonia and crossed the river Genusus (Albanian: *Shkumbin*) in 314 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] A few years later, Glaucias laid siege to Apollonia and captured the Greek colony of Epidamnos.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Illyrian Ardiaei tribe, centred in Montenegro, ruled over most of the territory of northern Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Their Ardiaean Kingdom reached its greatest extent under King Agron, the son of Pleuratus II.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Agron extended his rule over other neighbouring tribes as well.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Following Agron's death in 230 BC, his wife, Teuta, inherited the Ardiaean kingdom.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Teuta's forces extended their operations further southwards to the Ionian Sea.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 229 BC, Rome declared war on the kingdom for extensively plundering Roman ships.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The war ended in an Illyrian defeat in 227 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Teuta was eventually succeeded by Gentius in 181 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Gentius clashed with the Romans in 168 BC, initiating the Third Illyrian War.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The conflict resulted in the Roman conquest of the region by 167 BC.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Romans split the region into three administrative divisions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Roman Empire was split in 395 upon the death of Theodosius I into an Eastern and Western Roman Empire, in part because of the increasing pressure from threats during the Barbarian Invasions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] From the 6th century into the 7th century, the Slavs crossed the Danube and largely absorbed the indigenous Greeks, Illyrians, and Thracians in the Balkans; thus, the Illyrians were mentioned for the last time in historical records in the 7th century.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In the 11th century, the Great Schism formalised the break of communion between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Catholic Church, which is reflected in Albania through the emergence of a Catholic north and Orthodox south.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Albanian people inhabited the west of Lake Ochrida and the upper valley of the River Shkumbin and established the Principality of Arbanon in 1190 under the leadership of Progon of Kruja.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The realm was succeeded by his sons Gjin Progoni and Demetrio Progoni.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Upon the death of Dhimiter, the territory came under the rule of the Albanian-Greek Gregorios Kamonas and subsequently under the Golem of Kruja.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In the 13th century, the principality was dissolved.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Arbanon is considered to be the first sketch of an Albanian state, which retained a semi-autonomous status as the western extremity of the Byzantine Empire, under the Byzantine Doukai of Epirus or Laskarids of Nicaea.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Towards the end of the 12th and beginning of the 13th centuries, Serbs and Venetians began to take possession of the territory.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Albanians is uncertain; however, the first undisputed mention of Albanians dates back in historical records from 1079 or 1080 in a work by Michael Attaleiates, who referred to the Albanoi as having taken part in a revolt against Constantinople.
[src:alba/albania-p01] At this point, the Albanians were fully Christianised.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After the dissolution of Arbanon, Charles I of Anjou concluded an agreement with the Albanian rulers, promising to protect them and their ancient liberties.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1272, he established the Kingdom of Albania and conquered regions back from the Despotate of Epirus.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The kingdom claimed all of central Albania territory from Dyrrhachium along the Adriatic Sea coast down to Butrint.
[src:alba/albania-p01] A Catholic political structure was a basis for the papal plans of spreading Catholicism in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This plan also found the support of Helen of Anjou.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Around 30 Catholic churches and monasteries were built during her rule, mainly in northern Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Internal power struggles within the Byzantine Empire in the 14th century enabled Serbs' most powerful medieval ruler, Stefan Dušan, to establish a short-lived empire that included all of Albania except Durrës.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1367, Albanian rulers established the Despotate of Arta.
[src:alba/albania-p01] During that time, several Albanian principalities were established, notably the Principality of Albania, the Principality of Kastrioti, the Lordship of Berat, and the Principality of Dukagjini.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In the first half of the 15th century, the Ottoman Empire invaded most of Albania, and the League of Lezhë was organized under Skanderbeg as a ruler, who became the national hero of the Albanian medieval history.
[src:alba/albania-p01] that halted Ottoman advance into Europe for 25 years.
[src:alba/albania-p01] With the fall of Constantinople, the Ottoman Empire entered an extended period of military conquest and expansion, with its borders gradually expanding deep into Southeast Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1385, they reached the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, while in 1415, they established their garrisons across Southern Albania, eventually occupying most of Albania in 1431.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Thousands of Albanians consequently fled to Western Europe, particularly to Calabria, Naples, Ragusa, and Sicily, while numerous others sought protection at the often inaccessible Mountains of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Since the vast majority of Albanians were adherents of Christianity, they were considered an inferior class of people, resulting in them being discriminated against in various forms, including being subjected to heavy taxes.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Additionally, the Devshirme system allowed the Sultan to collect a requisite percentage of Christian adolescents from their families to compose the Janissary.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Ottoman conquest was also accompanied by the gradual process of Islamisation and the rapid construction of mosques.
[src:alba/albania-p01] A prosperous and longstanding revolution erupted after the formation of the League of Lezhë until the fall of Shkodër under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, who consistently defeated major Ottoman armies led by Sultans Murad II and Mehmed II.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Skanderbeg managed to unite several of the Albanian principalities, amongst them the Arianitis, Dukagjinis, Zaharias, and Thopias, and establish a centralised authority over most of the non-conquered territories, becoming the Lord of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Despite his competence as a military leader, Skanderbeg's victories over the Ottoman Empire's military had only a short-term impact, as his forces were unable to halt the Ottomans' advancement permanently; therefore, they successfully delayed the final conquest of Albanian lands only temporarily.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The constant Ottoman invasions caused enormous destruction to Albania, greatly reducing the population and destroying flocks of livestock and crops.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Besides surrender, there was no possible way Skanderbeg would be able to halt the Ottoman invasions despite his military forces achieving several consecutive victories against them.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Among other factors, his manpower and resources were insufficient for a prolonged war, preventing him from expanding the war efforts and driving the Turks from the Albanian borders.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania was therefore doomed to face an unending series of Ottoman attacks until it eventually fell years after his death.
[src:alba/albania-p01] When the Ottomans were gaining a firm foothold in the region, Albanian towns were organised into four principal sanjaks.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The government fostered trade by settling a sizeable Jewish colony of refugees fleeing persecution in Spain.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The city of Vlorë saw passing through its ports imported merchandise from Europe, such as velvets, cotton goods, mohairs, carpets, spices, and leather from Bursa and Constantinople.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Some citizens of Vlorë even had business associates throughout Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The phenomenon of Islamisation among the Albanians became primarily widespread from the 17th century and continued into the 18th century.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Islam offered them equal opportunities and advancement within the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alba/albania-p01] However, according to some scholars, motives for conversion were diverse depending on the context; although the lack of source material significantly hampers efforts to investigate such issues.
[src:alba/albania-p01] As a result of the Ottomans' increasing suppression of Catholicism, most Catholic Albanians converted in the 17th century, while Orthodox Albanians followed suit mainly in the following century.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Since the Albanian-inhabited regions were considered strategically important, Albanians made up a significant proportion of the Ottoman Empire's military and bureaucracy.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Consequently, many Muslim Albanians attained important political and military positions, while their work made a significant cultural contribution to the broader Muslim world.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Enjoying this privileged position, they held various high administrative positions, which, among others, included over two dozen Albanians serving as Grand viziers of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Additionally, other distinguished Albanians included members of the prominent Köprülü family, Zagan Pasha, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, and Ali Pasha of Tepelena.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Furthermore, two Ottoman sultans, Bayezid II and Mehmed III, were born to mothers of Albanian ethnic backgrounds.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Albanian Renaissance was a period with its roots in the late 18th century and continuing into the 19th century, during which the Albanian people gathered spiritual and intellectual strength for an independent cultural and political life within an independent nation.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Modern Albanian culture flourished too, especially Albanian literature and arts, and was frequently linked to the influences of the Romanticism and Enlightenment principles.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Prior to the rise of nationalism, Ottoman authorities suppressed any expression of national unity or conscience by the Albanian people.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The victory of Russia over the Ottoman Empire following the Russian-Ottoman Wars resulted the execution of the Treaty of San Stefano which assigned Albanian-populated lands to their Slavic and Greek neighbours.
[src:alba/albania-p01] However, the United Kingdom and Austro-Hungarian Empire consequently blocked the arrangement and caused the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:alba/albania-p01] From this point, Albanians started to organise themselves with the goal to protect and unite the Albanian-populated lands into a unitary nation, leading to the formation of the League of Prizren.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The league had initially the assistance of the Ottoman authorities whose position was based on the religious solidarity of Muslim people and landlords connected with the Ottoman administration.
[src:alba/albania-p01] They favoured and protected the Muslim solidarity and called for defence of Muslim lands simultaneously constituting the reason for titling the league Committee of the Real Muslims.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Approximately 300 Muslims participated in the assembly composed by delegates from Bosnia, the administrator of the Sanjak of Prizren as representatives of the central authorities and no delegates from Vilayet of Scutari.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Ottomans authorities cancelled their assistance when the league, under Abdyl Frashëri, became focused on working towards Albanian autonomy and requested merging four vilayets, including Kosovo, Shkodër, Monastir and Ioannina, into a unified vilayet, the Albanian Vilayet.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The league used military force to prevent the annexing areas of Plav and Gusinje assigned to Montenegro.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After several successful battles with Montenegrin troops, such as the Battle of Novšiće, the league was forced to retreat from their contested regions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The league was later defeated by the Ottoman army sent by the sultan.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania declared independence from the Ottoman Empire on 28 November 1912, accompanied by the establishment of the Senate and Government by the Assembly of Vlorë on 4 December 1912.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Its sovereignty was recognised by the Conference of London.
[src:alba/albania-p01] On 29 July 1913, the Treaty of London delineated the borders of the country and its neighbors, leaving many Albanians outside Albania, predominantly partitioned between Montenegro, Serbia, and Greece.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Headquartered in Vlorë, the International Commission of Control was established on 15 October 1913 to take care of the administration of Albania until its own political institutions were in order.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The International Gendarmerie was established as the Principality of Albania's first law enforcement agency.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In November, the first gendarmerie members arrived in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Prince of Albania Wilhelm of Wied *(Princ Vilhelm Vidi)* was selected as the first prince of the principality.
[src:alba/albania-p01] On 7 March, he arrived in the provisional capital of Durrës and began to organise his government, appointing Turhan Pasha Përmeti to form the first Albanian cabinet.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In November 1913, the Albanian pro-Ottoman forces had offered the throne of Albania to the Ottoman war minister of Albanian origin, Ahmed Izzet Pasha.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The pro-Ottoman peasants believed that the new regime was a tool of the six Christian Great Powers and local landowners, who owned half of the arable land.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In February 1914, the Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus was proclaimed in Gjirokastër by the local Greek population against incorporation to Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This initiative was short-lived, and in 1921 the southern provinces were incorporated into the Albanian Principality.
[src:alba/albania-p01] High-ranking Orthodox clergy were among the strongest opponents of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Reports from the period, including those from international observers, documented the burning of villages and civilian casualties.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Nationalist Orthodox insurgents were accused of targeting Muslim Albanian populations to consolidate territorial claims for Greece.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Meanwhile, the revolt of Albanian peasants against the new regime erupted under the leadership of the group of Muslim clerics gathered around Essad Pasha Toptani, who proclaimed himself the savior of Albania and Islam.
[src:alba/albania-p01] To gain the support of the Mirdita Catholic volunteers from northern Albania, Prince Wied appointed their leader, Prênk Bibë Doda, foreign minister of the Principality of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In May and June 1914, the International Gendarmerie was joined by Isa Boletini and his men, mostly from Kosovo, and the rebels defeated northern Mirdita Catholics, capturing most of Central Albania by the end of August 1914.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Prince Wied's regime collapsed, and he left the country on 3 September 1914.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The interwar period in Albania was marked by persistent economic and social difficulties, political instability and foreign interventions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After World War I, Albania lacked an established government and internationally recognised borders, rendering it vulnerable to neighboring entities such as Greece, Italy, and Yugoslavia, all of which sought to expand their influence.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This led to political uncertainty, highlighted in 1918 when the Congress of Durrës sought Paris Peace Conference protection but was denied, further complicating Albania's position on the international stage.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Territorial tensions escalated as Yugoslavia, particularly Serbia, sought control of northern Albania, while Greece aimed dominance in southern Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The situation deteriorated in 1919 when the Serbs launched attacks on Albanian inhabitants, among others in Gusinje and Plav, resulting in massacres and large-scale displacement.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Meanwhile, Italian influence continued to expand during this time, driven by economic interests and political ambitions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Fan Noli, renowned for his idealism, became prime minister in 1924, with a vision to institute a Western-style constitutional government, abolish feudalism, counter Italian influence, and enhance critical sectors, including infrastructure, education and healthcare.
[src:alba/albania-p01] He faced resistance from former allies, who had assisted in the removal of Zog from power, and struggled to secure foreign aid to implement his agenda.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Noli's decision to establish diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union, an adversary of the Serbian elite, ignited allegations of bolshevism from Belgrade.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This in turn led to increased pressure from Italy and culminated in Zog's restoration to authority.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1928, Zog transitioned Albania from a republic to a monarchy that garnered backing from Fascist Italy, with Zog assuming the title of King Zog I.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Key constitutional changes dissolved the Senate and established a unicameral National Assembly while preserving Zog's authoritative powers.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1939, Italy under Benito Mussolini launched a military invasion of Albania, resulting in the exile of Zog and the creation of an Italian protectorate.
[src:alba/albania-p01] As World War II progressed, Italy aimed to expand its territorial dominion in the Balkans, including territorial claims on regions of Greece (Chameria), Macedonia, Montenegro and Kosovo.
[src:alba/albania-p01] These ambitions laid the foundation of Greater Albania, which aimed to unite all areas with Albanian-majority populations into a single country.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1943, as Italy's control declined, Nazi Germany assumed control of Albania, subjecting Albanians to forced labour, economic exploitation and repression under German rule.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This period saw the forced expulsion and massacres of the Cham Albanians, a predominantly Muslim group.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The religious divide was used as a justification for violence, with some Orthodox locals reportedly identifying Muslim neighbors to paramilitary groups, leading to massacres and the forced expulsion of thousands.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The tide shifted in 1944 when Albanian partisan forces, under the leadership of Enver Hoxha and other communist leaders, successfully liberated Albania from German occupation.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The establishment of the People's Republic of Albania under the leadership of Enver Hoxha was a significant epoch in modern Albanian history.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Hoxha's regime embraced Marxist–Leninist ideologies and implemented authoritarian policies, including prohibition of religious practices, severe restrictions on travel, and abolition of private property rights.
[src:alba/albania-p01] It was also defined by a persistent pattern of purges, extensive repression, instances of betrayal, and hostility to external influences.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Any form of opposition or resistance to his rule was met with expeditious and severe consequences, such as internal exile, extended imprisonment, and execution.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The regime confronted a multitude of challenges, including widespread poverty, illiteracy, health crises and gender inequality.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In response, Hoxha initiated a modernisation initiative aimed at attaining economic and social liberation and transforming Albania into an industrial society.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania's diplomatic history under Hoxha was characterised by notable conflicts.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Initially aligned with Yugoslavia as a satellite state, the relationship deteriorated as Yugoslavia aimed to incorporate Albania within its territory.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Subsequently, Albania established relations with the Soviet Union and engaged trade agreements with other Eastern European countries, but experienced disagreements over Soviet policies, leading to strained ties with Moscow and diplomatic separation in 1961.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Simultaneously, tensions with the West heightened due to Albania's refusal to hold free elections and allegations of Western support for anti-communist uprisings.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania's enduring partnership was with China; it sided with Beijing during the Sino-Soviet conflict, resulting in severed ties with the Soviet Union and withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact in response to the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:alba/albania-p01] But their relations stagnated in 1970, prompting both to reassess their commitment, and Albania actively reduced its dependence on China.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Under Hoxha's regime, Albania underwent a widespread campaign targeting religious clergy of various faiths, resulting in public persecution and executions, particularly targeting Muslims, Roman Catholics and Eastern Orthodox adherents.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 1946, religious estates underwent nationalisation, coinciding with the closure or transformation of religious institutions into various other purposes.
[src:alba/albania-p01] This culminated in 1976, when Albania became the world's first constitutionally atheist state.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Under this regime, citizens were forced to renounce their religious beliefs, adopt a secular way of life, and embrace socialist ideology.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After four decades of communism paired with the revolutions of 1989, Albania witnessed a notable rise in political activism, particularly among students, which led to a transformation in the prevailing order.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After the first multi-party elections of 1991, the communist party maintained a stronghold in the parliament until its defeat in the parliamentary elections of 1992 directed by the Democratic Party.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Considerable economic and financial resources were devoted to pyramid schemes that were widely supported by the government.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The schemes swept up somewhere between one sixth and one third of the population of the country.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Despite the International Monetary Fund's warnings, Sali Berisha defended the schemes as large investment firms, leading more people to redirect their remittances and sell their homes and cattle for cash to deposit in the schemes.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The schemes began to collapse in late 1996, leading many of the investors to join initially peaceful protests against the government, requesting their money back.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The protests turned violent in February 1997 as government forces responded by firing on the demonstrators.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In March, the Police and Republican Guard deserted, leaving their armories open.
[src:alba/albania-p01] These were promptly emptied by militias and criminal gangs.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The resulting civil war caused a wave of evacuations of foreign nationals and refugees.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The crisis led both Aleksandër Meksi and Sali Berisha to resign from office in the wake of the general election.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In April 1997, Operation Alba, a U.N. peacekeeping force led by Italy, entered Albania with two goals: to assist with the evacuation of expatriates and secure the ground for international organisations.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The main international organisation involved was the Western European Union's multinational Albanian Police element, which worked with the government to restructure the judicial system and simultaneously the Albanian police.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After the fall of the communist system, Albania pursued integration with Euro-Atlantic institutions.
[src:alba/albania-p01] It formally applied for membership of the European Union on 28 April 2009 and joined NATO the same year.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania was granted EU candidate status in June 2014, while accession negotiations began with the first intergovernmental conference in July 2022.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Albania opened negotiations on the fundamentals cluster in October 2024 and, by late 2025, had opened all negotiating clusters, a development described by the European Commission as a significant milestone in the accession process.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The 2013 Albanian parliamentary election ended eight years of Democratic Party rule under Sali Berisha.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Socialist Party, led by Edi Rama, won the election as the main force of the Alliance for a European Albania, with the Socialist Movement for Integration as a coalition partner.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Rama's governments promoted judicial reform, public administration changes, urban redevelopment, digitalisation of public services, tourism development and EU accession as central priorities.
[src:alba/albania-p01] A major justice reform package adopted in 2016 created new institutions including the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime (SPAK), which later became central to the prosecution of high-level corruption and organised crime cases.
[src:alba/albania-p01] At the same time, Rama's long tenure became increasingly controversial.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The Socialist Party won the 2017, 2021 and 2025 parliamentary elections, making Rama the first Albanian prime minister to secure four consecutive mandates.
[src:alba/albania-p01] His dominance was accompanied by persistent criticism from opposition parties, civil society and international monitors over corruption, weak checks and balances, state capture, media pressure and the use of state resources in elections.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Freedom House has classified Albania as "Partly Free" and as a "Transitional or Hybrid Regime", while noting that elections are competitive but that politics is highly polarised, organised around dominant personalities, and affected by corruption and bribery.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Freedom House's *Nations in Transit* assessment described Albania's national governance as democratic but dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities, and stated that elections were frequently marred by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Concerns about state capture also became a recurring theme in assessments of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation published *Deconstructing State Capture in Albania*, a report examining grand corruption cases and "tailor-made laws" from 2008 to 2020.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The report argued that state-capture mechanisms in Albania involved clientelist networks, corruption in the judiciary and laws designed to benefit particular private interests.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Electoral integrity remained disputed during Rama's later terms.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights stated that the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election was competitive and professionally managed, but that it took place in a highly polarised environment and contestants did not enjoy a level playing field.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The final report cited reports of intimidation, misuse of public resources and pressure on public employees, which undermined equal opportunities.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Reuters reported that the 2025 campaign was dominated by Rama's promise to secure EU membership by 2030 and by accusations of widespread corruption, while critics argued that he had concentrated too much power.
[src:alba/albania-p01] After the election, Rama began his fourth term in September 2025 and declared EU membership by 2030 the central goal of his mandate.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The consolidation of Rama's rule coincided with a wave of investigations by SPAK against high-ranking figures from both the governing majority and the opposition.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Deputy prime minister and infrastructure minister Belinda Balluku was later investigated over public-tender allegations, denied wrongdoing, and was dismissed by Rama in February 2026 as the case intensified.
[src:alba/albania-p01] European Union officials praised SPAK's work as central to rule-of-law reform, while also warning that Albania's EU progress depended on judicial independence and credible anti-corruption results.
[src:alba/albania-p01] On 26 November 2019, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake struck Albania, with the epicentre about 16 km (10 mi) southwest of Mamurras.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The tremor was felt in Tirana and in places as far away as Taranto, Italy, and Belgrade, Serbia, while the most affected areas were Durrës and Kodër-Thumanë.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The response included humanitarian aid from the Albanian diaspora and several foreign governments.
[src:alba/albania-p01] On 9 March 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p01] In 2026, large anti-government demonstrations known as the Flamingo Revolution emerged after proposed luxury coastal developments on Sazan Island and the Zvërnec peninsula, including projects linked to Jared Kushner, became a focus of environmental and anti-corruption protests.
[src:alba/albania-p01] Demonstrators accused Rama's government of lacking transparency, endangering protected ecosystems and failing to tackle corruption or improve public services.
[src:alba/albania-p01] The protests, initially centred on environmental protection, expanded into broader demands for government accountability, early elections and Rama's resignation.
[src:alba/albania-p01] European Parliament figures also warned that the coastal-development plans could affect Albania's EU accession process if they conflicted with environmental obligations and democratic standards.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania lies along the Mediterranean Sea on the Balkan Peninsula in South and Southeast Europe, and has an area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi).
[src:alba/albania-p02] It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea to the west, Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, Greece to the south, and the Ionian Sea to the southwest.
[src:alba/albania-p02] It is between latitudes 42° and 39° N and longitudes 21° and 19° E.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Geographic coordinates include Vërmosh at 42° 35' 34" northern latitude as the northernmost point, Konispol at 39° 40' 0" northern latitude as the southernmost, Sazan at 19° 16' 50" eastern longitude as the westernmost, and Vërnik at 21° 1' 26" eastern longitude as the easternmost.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Mount Korab, rising at 2,764 m (9,068.24 ft) above the Adriatic, is the highest point, while the Mediterranean Sea, at 0 m (0.00 ft), is the lowest.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country extends 148 km (92 mi) from east to west and around 340 km (211 mi) from north to south.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania has a diverse and varied landscape with mountains and hills that traverse its territory in various directions.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country is home to extensive mountain ranges, including the Albanian Alps in the north, the Korab Mountains in the east, the Pindus Mountains in the southeast, the Ceraunian Mountains in the southwest, and the Skanderbeg Mountains in the centre.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In the northwest is the Lake of Shkodër, Southern Europe's largest lake.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Towards the southeast emerges the Lake of Ohrid, one of the world's oldest continuously existing lakes.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Farther south, the expanse includes the Large and Small Lake of Prespa, some of the Balkans' highest lakes.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Rivers rise mostly in the east and discharge into the Adriatic and Ionian Seas.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country's longest river, measured from mouth to source, is the Drin, which starts at the confluence of its two headwaters, the Black and White Drin.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Of particular concern is the Vjosë, one of Europe's last intact large river systems.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In Albania forest cover is around 29.% of the total land area, equivalent to 788,900 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 788,800 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Of the naturally regenerating forest 11% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:alba/albania-p02] For the year 2015, 97% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 3% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The climate of Albania exhibits a distinguished level of variability and diversity due to the differences in latitude, longitude and altitude.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania experiences a Mediterranean and Continental climate, characterised by the presence of four distinct seasons.
[src:alba/albania-p02] According to the Köppen classification, Albania encompasses five primary climatic types, spanning from Mediterranean and subtropical in the western half to oceanic, continental and subarctic in the eastern half of the country.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The coastal regions along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas in Albania are acknowledged as the warmest areas, while the northern and eastern regions encompassing the Albanian Alps and the Korab Mountains are recognised as the coldest areas in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Throughout the year, the average monthly temperatures fluctuate, ranging from −1 °C (30 °F) during the winter months to 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) in the summer months.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Notably, the highest recorded temperature of 43.9 °C (111.0 °F) was observed in Kuçovë on 18 July 1973, while the lowest temperature of −29 °C (−20 °F) was recorded in Shtyllë, Librazhd on 9 January 2017.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania receives most of the precipitation in winter months and less in summer months.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The average precipitation is about 1,485 millimetres (58.5 inches).
[src:alba/albania-p02] The mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 and 3,000 millimetres (24 and 118 inches) depending on geographical location.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The northwestern and southeastern highlands receive the intenser amount of precipitation, whilst the northeastern and southwestern highlands as well as the Western Lowlands the more limited amount.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The Albanian Alps in the far north of the country are considered to be among the most humid regions of Europe, receiving at least 3,100 mm (122.0 in) of rain annually.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Four glaciers within these mountains were discovered at a relatively low altitude of 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), which is extremely rare for such a southerly latitude.
[src:alba/albania-p02] A biodiversity hotspot, Albania possesses an exceptionally rich and contrasting biodiversity on account of its geographical location at the centre of the Mediterranean Sea and the great diversity in its climatic, geological and hydrological conditions.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The estuaries, wetlands and lakes are extraordinarily important for the greater flamingo, pygmy cormorant and the extremely rare and perhaps the most iconic bird of the country, the dalmatian pelican.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Of particular importance are the Mediterranean monk seal, loggerhead sea turtle and green sea turtle that use to nest on the country's coastal waters and shores.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In terms of phytogeography, Albania is part of the Boreal Kingdom and stretches specifically within the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal and Mediterranean Region.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Its territory can be subdivided into four terrestrial ecoregions of the Palearctic realm namely within the Illyrian deciduous forests, Balkan mixed forests, Pindus Mountains mixed forests and Dinaric Mountains mixed forests.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Approximately 3,500 different species of plants can be found in Albania which refers principally to a Mediterranean and Eurasian character.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country maintains a vibrant tradition of herbal and medicinal practices.
[src:alba/albania-p02] At the minimum 300 plants growing locally are used in the preparation of herbs and medicines.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The trees within the forests are primarily fir, oak, beech and pine.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania has been an active participant in numerous international agreements and conventions aimed at strengthing its commitment to the preservation and sustainable management of biological diversity.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since 1994, the country is a party to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and its associated Cartagena and Nagoya Protocols.
[src:alba/albania-p02] To uphold these commitments, it has developed and implemented a comprehensive National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan (NBSAP).
[src:alba/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania has established a partnership with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), advancing its conservation efforts on both national and international scales.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Guided by the IUCN, the country has made substantial progress in the foundation of protected areas within its boundaries, encompassing 12 national parks among others Butrint, Karaburun-Sazan, Llogara, Prespa and Vjosa.
[src:alba/albania-p02] As a signatory to the Ramsar Convention, Albania has granted special recognition upon four wetlands, designating them as Wetlands of International Importance, including Buna-Shkodër, Butrint, Karavasta and Prespa.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country's dedication to protection extends further into the sphere of UNESCO's World Network of Biosphere Reserves, operating within the framework of the Man and the Biosphere Programme, evidenced by its engagement in the Ohrid-Prespa Transboundary Biosphere Reserve.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania is host to two natural World Heritage Sites, which encompass the Ohrid region and both the Gashi River and Rrajca as part of Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The protected areas of Albania are areas designated and managed by the Albanian government.
[src:alba/albania-p02] There are 12 national parks, 4 ramsar sites, 1 biosphere reserve and 786 other types of conservation reserves in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Located in the north, the Albanian Alps National Park, comprising the former Theth National Park and Valbonë Valley National Park, is surrounded amidst the towering peaks of the Albanian Alps.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In the east, portions of the rugged Korab, Nemërçka and Shebenik Mountains are conserved within the boundaries of Fir of Hotovë-Dangëlli National Park, Shebenik National Park and Prespa National Park, with the latter encompassing Albania's share of the Great and Small Lakes of Prespa.
[src:alba/albania-p02] To the south, the Ceraunian Mountains define the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, shaping the landscape of Llogara National Park, which extends into the Karaburun Peninsula, forming the Karaburun-Sazan Marine Park.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Further southward lies Butrint National Park, occupying a peninsula surrounded by the Lake of Butrint and the Channel of Vivari.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In the west, stretching along the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast, the Divjakë-Karavasta National Park boasts the extensive Lagoon of Karavasta, one of the largest lagoon systems in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Notably, Europe's first wild river national park, Vjosa National Park, safeguards the Vjosa River and its primary tributaries, which originates in the Pindus Mountains and flows to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Dajti Mountain National Park, Lurë-Dejë Mountain National Park and Tomorr Mountain National Park protect the mountainous terrain of the centre of Albania, including the Tomorr and Skanderbeg Mountains.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Environmental issues in Albania notably encompass air and water pollution, climate change impacts, waste management shortcomings, biodiversity loss and imperative for nature conservation.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Climate change is predicted to exert significant impacts on the quality of life in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania is one of the European countries most at risk and vulnerable to natural disasters.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Natural disasters, such as floods, forest fires, and landslides, are increasing in Albania due to climate change, causing significant damage.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Rising sea levels are anticipated to negatively impact coastal communities and the tourism industry.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2023 Albania emitted 7.67 million tonnes of greenhouse gases, equivalent to 2.73 tonnes per person, making it a relatively low emitting country.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania has pledged a 20.9% reduction in GHG emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country has a moderate and improving performance in the Environmental Performance Index with an overall ranking of 62 out of 180 countries in 2022.
[src:alba/albania-p02] However, Albania's ranking has decreased since its highest placement at position 15 in the Environmental Performance Index of 2012.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since declaring independence in 1912, Albania has undergone several major constitutional transformations, including a monarchy, a communist one-party state, and, following the collapse of communism, the establishment of a democratic parliamentary republic.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The current constitutional order was established with the adoption of the Constitution of Albania in 1998, creating a parliamentary constitutional republic based on the separation of powers between the legislature, executive and judiciary.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Executive authority is exercised by the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers, while the President of Albania serves as head of state with largely ceremonial and constitutional responsibilities.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Legislative authority is vested in the unicameral Parliament of Albania, elected every four years through proportional representation.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Judicial authority is exercised by an independent judiciary headed by the Constitutional Court and the Supreme Court.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since Edi Rama and the Socialist Party of Albania came to power in 2013, Albania has experienced an unprecedented concentration of executive power, with the Socialist Party winning four consecutive parliamentary elections in 2013, 2017, 2021 and 2025.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Supporters credit Rama's governments with accelerating European Union accession negotiations, implementing the 2016 justice reform, expanding digital public services, improving infrastructure and increasing tourism.
[src:alba/albania-p02] At the same time, Rama's prolonged tenure has generated sustained domestic and international criticism.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Opposition parties, civil society organisations and a number of analysts have argued that Albania has experienced significant democratic backsliding characterised by increasing executive dominance, weakened institutional checks and balances, clientelist governance and extensive political patronage.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Freedom House describes Albania as a "Partly Free" country and notes that politics is dominated by powerful party leaders, while corruption remains a persistent challenge.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Its *Nations in Transit* report characterises Albania's national governance as being dominated by clientelist party politics and states that elections continue to be affected by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Concerns regarding state capture have also featured prominently in assessments of Albania's political system.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Electoral integrity has remained a contentious issue.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Following the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election, the OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights concluded that the election was competitive and professionally managed, but found that it was held in a highly polarised environment without a level playing field.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The observation mission reported misuse of public resources, pressure on public employees, intimidation allegations and unequal campaign conditions that undermined equal opportunities among contestants.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The European Commission has generally praised SPAK's work while continuing to stress that corruption remains prevalent in many sectors and that judicial independence must be protected from political pressure.
[src:alba/albania-p02] During Rama's fourth term, anti-government demonstrations intensified.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Beginning in late 2025 and expanding further during the Flamingo Revolution in 2026, protesters accused the government of systemic corruption, lack of transparency, misuse of public resources and favouring politically connected business interests.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The protests, initially triggered by opposition to coastal development projects, evolved into broader demands for democratic reform, government accountability and Rama's resignation.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Human rights protections are guaranteed by the Constitution regardless of ethnicity, language, race or religion.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Nevertheless, international organisations continue to identify concerns regarding judicial independence, corruption, media pluralism and political influence over state institutions, while noting that progress in these areas remains closely linked to Albania's European Union accession process.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Emerging from decades of isolation following the fall of communism, Albania has adopted a foreign policy orientation centred on active cooperation and engagement in international affairs.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The external affairs of Albania underscore the country's dedication to regional stability and integration into major international institutions.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1955, shortly after emerging from a period of isolation during the communist era.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The country reached a major achievement in its foreign policy by securing NATO membership in 2009.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since obtaining candidate status in 2014, the country has also embarked on a comprehensive reform agenda to align itself with European Union (EU) accession standards, with the objective of becoming an EU member state.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania and Kosovo maintain a fraternal relationship strengthened by their substantial cultural, ethnical and historical ties.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Both countries foster enduring diplomatic ties, with Albania actively supporting Kosovo's development and international integration efforts.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Its fundamental contribution to Kosovo's path to independence is underscored by its early recognition of Kosovo's sovereignty in 2008.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Furthermore, both governments hold annual joint meetings, displayed by the inaugural meeting in 2014, which serves as an official platform to enhance bilateral cooperation and reinforce their joint commitment to policies that promote the stability and prosperity of the broader Albanian region.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The Albanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air and Naval Forces and constitute the military and paramilitary forces of the country.
[src:alba/albania-p02] They are led by a commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defence and by the President as the supreme commander during wartime.
[src:alba/albania-p02] However, in times of peace its powers are executed through the Prime Minister and the Defence Minister.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The chief purpose of the armed forces of Albania is the defence of the independence, the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of the country, as well as the participation in humanitarian, combat, non-combat and peace support operations.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Military service is voluntary since 2010 with the age of 19 being the legal minimum age for the duty.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania has committed to increase the participations in multinational operations.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since the fall of communism, the country has participated in six international missions but only one United Nations mission in Georgia, where it sent three military observers.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since February 2008, Albania has participated officially in NATO's Operation Active Endeavor in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:alba/albania-p02] It was invited to join NATO on 3 April 2008, and it became a full member on 2 April 2009.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania reduced the number of active troops from 65,000 in 1988 to 14,500 in 2009.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The military now consists mainly of a small fleet of aircraft and sea vessels.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Increasing the military budget was one of the most important conditions for NATO integration.
[src:alba/albania-p02] As of 1996 military spending was an estimated 1.5% of the country's GDP, only to peak in 2009 at 2% and fall again to 1.5%.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Human rights in Albania are formally protected by the Constitution of Albania, which guarantees equality before the law, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, religious freedom and protection from discrimination.
[src:alba/albania-p02] International assessments generally describe Albania as a competitive but weakened democracy, with persistent problems involving corruption, political pressure on institutions, media freedom, gender-based violence, prison conditions and discrimination against vulnerable groups.
[src:alba/albania-p02] During the long premiership of Edi Rama, whose Socialist Party of Albania has governed since 2013, human-rights concerns have often been linked to broader criticism of democratic backsliding, concentration of executive power, clientelist party politics and weak institutional checks.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Freedom House classifies Albania as "Partly Free" and states that corruption and bribery remain major problems, while its *Nations in Transit* assessment describes national governance as dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Opposition parties and critics have characterised Rama's rule as increasingly authoritarian, while the government and its supporters point to judicial reform, European Union accession progress and the work of anti-corruption institutions as evidence of democratic consolidation.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Freedom of expression and media independence remain major concerns.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The United States Department of State's 2024 human-rights report identified serious restrictions on freedom of expression and media freedom, including journalist self-censorship, threats and smear campaigns against journalists reporting on alleged corruption.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists in Albania face political pressure, especially during elections, as well as pressure from media owners and economic insecurity.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In the 2026 World Press Freedom Index, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries, with media-rights groups noting continued structural problems affecting editorial independence and journalist safety.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Freedom of assembly is generally recognised, but protest policing has drawn attention during periods of political unrest.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Authorities said the police response followed attacks on officers and damage to property, while protesters and opposition figures accused the government of using force to suppress dissent.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Corruption also has direct implications for human rights and public trust in institutions.
[src:alba/albania-p02] International reports have repeatedly identified corruption in government, law enforcement, the judiciary and local administration as a major problem.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation argued that Albania showed signs of state capture through grand corruption, clientelist networks and tailor-made laws benefiting private interests.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Conditions in prisons and detention facilities have remained a human-rights concern.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Amnesty International reported that people in prisons experienced overcrowding and inadequate healthcare, while the Council of Europe and Albanian authorities have identified prison reform and protection of prisoners' rights as continuing priorities.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Civil-society submissions to the UN Committee against Torture have also raised concerns about overcrowding, poor detention conditions, limited access to legal representation and insufficient investigation of abuse allegations.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Violence against women and girls remains widespread.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Nearly 60% of women in rural areas suffer physical or psychological violence and nearly 8% are victims of sexual violence.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2014 the Albanian Helsinki Committee (AHC) reported that the number of female murder victims remained high.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The Commissioner for Protection from Discrimination has raised concerns regarding the family registration law that discriminates against women.
[src:alba/albania-p02] As a result, heads of households, who are overwhelmingly men, have the right to change family residency without their partners' permission.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe's GREVIO monitoring body reported progress in Albania's framework against violence against women, but said serious gaps remained, including persistent gender stereotypes, extremely low reporting of sexual violence and limited specialist services.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2026, the United Nations in Albania welcomed the adoption of a new law on prevention and protection from violence against women and domestic violence.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Roma, Balkan Egyptian and other minority communities continue to face barriers in education, housing, employment and access to public services.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2024, the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination reviewed Albania's implementation of anti-discrimination obligations and discussed the situation of Roma and Egyptian communities, including education, legal aid and hate-speech monitoring.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania has legal protections against discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, and LGBT organisations hold public events such as Tirana Pride.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In 2015, ILGA-Europe ranked Albania 19th in terms of LGBT rights out of 49 observed European countries.
[src:alba/albania-p02] In the 2022 Rainbow Europe report, lack of progress caused Albania to be ranked 28th among 49 countries.
[src:alba/albania-p02] ILGA-Europe's later country reporting continued to identify discrimination and unsafe school environments for LGBTI people, with a 2024–2025 nationwide survey by Aleanca LGBTI reporting that most respondents viewed schools as unsafe for marginalised groups, including LGBTI students.
[src:alba/albania-p02] are the first-level administrative units in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Albania is defined within a territorial area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi) in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:alba/albania-p02] It is informally divided into three regions, the Northern, Central and Southern Regions.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Since its Declaration of Independence in 1912, Albania has reformed its internal organisation 21 times.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Presently, the primary administrative units are the twelve constituent counties (*qarqe/qarqet*), which hold equal status under the law.
[src:alba/albania-p02] Counties had previously been used in the 1950s and were recreated on 31 July 2000 to unify the 36 districts (*rrathë/rrathët*) of that time.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The largest county in Albania by population is Tirana County with over 800,000 people.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The smallest county, by population, is Gjirokastër County with over 70,000 people.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The largest county, by area, is Korçë County encompassing 3,711 square kilometres (1,433 sq mi) of the southeast of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The smallest county, by area, is Durrës County with an area of 766 square kilometres (296 sq mi) in the west of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p02] The counties are made up of 61 second-level divisions known as municipalities (*bashki/bashkia*).
[src:alba/albania-p02] The municipalities are the first level of local governance, responsible for local needs and law enforcement.
[src:alba/albania-p02] They unified and simplified the previous system of urban and rural municipalities or communes (*komuna/komunat*) in 2015.
[src:alba/albania-p02] For smaller issues of local government, the municipalities are organised into 373 administrative units (*njësia*/*njësitë administrative*).
[src:alba/albania-p02] There are also 2980 villages (*fshatra/fshatrat*), neighborhoods or wards (*lagje/lagjet*), and localities (*lokalitete/lokalitetet*) previously used as administrative units.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Transitioning from a socialist planned to a capitalist mixed economy, Albania is classified as a developing open market with an upper-middle income status.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Albanian economy is characterised by a substantial service sector, comprising 48.6% of GDP, with key contributions from wholesale and retail trade, tourism, real estate, and logistics.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Following this, the industrial sector accounts for 20.2%, particularly influenced by construction, while the agricultural sector, including forestry, and fisheries, represents 18.5%, and the manufacturing sector contributes a modest 6.3% to the economy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] As of 2025, Albania's nominal gross domestic product (GDP) is reported at $26.911 billion with a GDP per capita of $9,474.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The projected annual percentage change in economic growth for 2025 is 3.8%, with a forecasted moderation to 3.5% by 2029.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania has developed a comprehensive framework for international trade through several pivotal agreements with various regions.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Stabilisation and Association Agreement (SAA) with the European Union (EU), signed in 2006, is one of the most significant.
[src:alba/albania-p03] This agreement provides critical trade benefits and serves as a foundation for the Albanian integration into the EU.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania signed a free trade agreement (FTA) with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which further expands trade opportunities and market access.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country is also a signatory to the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) and Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC), promoting regional trade and collaboration with neighboring countries.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Furthermore, the country has enhanced its bilateral trade relations through a FTA with Turkey, the United Kingdom and a bilateral investment treaty with the United States.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The 2023 Economic Freedom of the World report placed Albania in the 31st position, noting a considerable degree of economic independence and the effective adoption of market-oriented policies.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The 2024 Bertelsmann Transformation Index ranked Albania 20th and acknowledged substantial progress in political and economic transformation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Also in 2024, the country was positioned 23rd in the Global Gender Gap Index, excelling in the Economic Participation and Opportunity category with a global ranking of 16th, showcasing significant advancements in women's economic participation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] However, the Albanian economy, despite demonstrating considerable resilience, encounters substantial vulnerabilities that hinder its development.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Principal challenges include widespread corruption, distorted competition, and frequent modifications to fiscal legislation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Furthermore, inadequate contract enforcement, a large informal sector, and persistent labor shortages further complicate the national economic progress.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Economic landscape of Albania is characterised by regional disparities, particularly apparent in the concentration of economic activities in the triangular region formed by Tirana, Durrës and Laç.
[src:alba/albania-p03] This metropolitan area, referred to as Durana, functions as the principal economic center of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In the year 2021, Tirana County accounted for a significant 44% of the national GDP, with the counties of Fier and Durrës also playing integral roles in the economy, contributing 11% and 10% to the GDP, respectively.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Other substantial economic centers, such as Elbasan and the coastal cities of Sarandë and Vlorë, highlight the uneven distribution of economic development across the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Cultural regions, including Berat and Korçë, despite their geographical distance from the primary economic hubs, have derived considerable benefits from the expansion of the tourism sector.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Concerns over illicit finance, money laundering and organised-crime influence have become increasingly prominent in assessments of Albania's economy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The United States Department of State has identified Albania as vulnerable to money laundering, with criminal proceeds laundered through real estate purchases, construction projects, virtual assets and business development.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Its 2025 Investment Climate Statement also described Albania's economic development as vulnerable because of widespread corruption, organised crime, distorted competition, labour shortages, low productivity and a large informal sector.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime's 2025 Global Organized Crime Index described Albania as a prominent destination for money laundering, stating that criminal organisations exploit the real estate, tourism and construction sectors to legitimise illicit profits.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It also reported that the construction sector is heavily infiltrated by illicit funds, distorting the market, and that corruption within political and law-enforcement institutions continues to facilitate organised crime.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The government has generally rejected accusations of political protection for organised crime and has pointed to justice reform, anti-money-laundering measures and investigations by the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime as evidence of progress.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Further, the country is a worldwide significant producer of salvia, rosemary and yellow gentian.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country's proximity to the Ionian Sea and the Adriatic Sea give the underdeveloped fishing industry great potential.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The World Bank and European Community economists report that, Albania's fishing industry has good potential to generate export earnings because prices in the nearby Greek and Italian markets are many times higher than those in the Albanian market.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The fish available off the coasts of the country are carp, trout, sea bream, mussels and crustaceans.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania has one of Europe's longest histories of viticulture.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Today's region was one of the few places where vine was naturally grown during the ice age.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The oldest found seeds in the region are 4,000 to 6,000 years old.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2009, the nation produced an estimated 17,500 tonnes of wine.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania's secondary sector has undergone many changes and diversification since the communist regime collapsed.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It is very diversified, from electronics, manufacturing, textiles, to food, cement, mining, and energy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Antea Cement plant in Fushë-Krujë is considered one of the nation's largest industrial greenfield investments.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian oil and gas is one of the most promising, albeit strictly regulated, sectors of its economy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania has the second-largest oil deposits in the Balkan peninsula after Romania, and the largest oil reserves in Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Albpetrol company is owned by the Albanian state and monitors the state petroleum agreements in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The textile industry has seen an extensive expansion by approaching companies from the European Union (EU) in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to the Instituti i Statistikës (INSTAT), as of 2016, textile production had an annual growth of 5.3% and an annual turnover of around 1.5 billion euros.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania is a significant minerals producer and ranks among the world's leading chromium producers and exporters.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The nation is also a notable producer of copper, nickel, and coal.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Batra mine, Bulqizë mine, and Thekna mine are among the most recognised Albanian mines still in operation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The tertiary sector represents the fastest growing sector of the country's economy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] 36% of the population work in the service sector which contributes to 65% of the country's GDP.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Ever since the end of the 20th century, the banking industry is a major component of the tertiary sector and remains in good conditions overall due to privatisation and the commendable monetary policy.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Previously one of the most isolated and controlled countries in the world, telecommunication industry represents nowadays another major contributor to the sector.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It developed largely through privatisation and subsequent investment by both domestic and foreign investors.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Eagle, Vodafone and Telekom Albania are the leading telecommunications service providers in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Tourism is recognised as an industry of national importance and has been steadily increasing since the beginnings of the 21st century.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It directly accounted for 8.4% of GDP in 2016 though including indirect contributions pushes the proportion to 26%.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In the same year, the country received approximately 4.74 million visitors mostly from across Europe and the United States as well.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The increase of foreign visitors has been dramatic.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania had only 500,000 visitors in 2005, and an estimated 4.2 million in 2012, an increase of 740 percent.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UN Tourism), Albania welcomed approximately 11.7 million tourists in 2024, marking a significant increase from previous years.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The bulk of the tourist industry is concentrated along the Adriatic and Ionian Sea in the west of the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] But the Albanian Riviera in the southwest has the most scenic and pristine beaches; its coastline has a considerable length of 446 kilometres (277 miles).
[src:alba/albania-p03] The coast has a distinctive character, rich in varieties of virgin beaches, capes, coves, covered bays, lagoons, small gravel beaches, sea caves, and many landforms.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Some parts of this seaside are very clean ecologically, including unexplored areas, which are very rare within the Mediterranean.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Other attractions include the mountainous areas such as the Albanian Alps, Ceraunian Mountains and Korab Mountains but also the historical cities of Berat, Durrës, Gjirokastër, Sarandë, Shkodër and Korçë.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The international airport of Tirana is the premier air gateway to the country, and is also the principal hub for Albania's national flag carrier airline, Air Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The airport carried more than 3.3 million passengers in 2019 with connections to many destinations in other countries around Europe, Africa and Asia.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country plans to progressively increase the number of airports especially in the south with possible locations in Sarandë, Gjirokastër and Vlorë.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The highways and motorways in Albania are properly maintained and often still under construction and renovation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Autostrada 1 (A1) is an integral transportation corridor and the country's longest motorway.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It is planned to link Durrës on the Adriatic Sea across Pristina in Kosovo with the Pan-European Corridor X in Serbia.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Autostrada 2 (A2) is part of the Adriatic–Ionian Corridor as well as the Pan-European Corridor VIII and connects Fier with Vlorë.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Autostrada 3 (A3) is under construction and after its completion will connect Tirana and Elbasan with the Pan-European Corridor VIII.
[src:alba/albania-p03] When all three corridors are completed, Albania will have an estimated 759 kilometres (472 mi) of highway, linking it with all neighboring countries.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Durrës is the busiest and largest seaport in the country, followed by Vlorë, Shëngjin and Sarandë.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The rail network is administered by the national railway company Hekurudha Shqiptare.
[src:alba/albania-p03] A new railway line from Tirana and its airport to Durrës is planned.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The location of this railway, connecting Albania's most populated urban areas, makes it an important economic development project.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Due to its location and natural resources, Albania has a wide variety of energy resources, ranging from gas, oil, and coal to wind, solar, water, and other renewable sources.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to the World Economic Forum's 2023 Energy Transition Index (ETI), the country ranked 21st globally, highlighting the progress in its energy transition agenda.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Currently, Albania's electricity generation sector depends on hydroelectricity, ranking fifth in the world in percentage terms.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Increasing risks of river floods and droughts due to climate change is expected to put electricity generation at risk.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Drin, in the north, hosts four hydroelectric power stations, including Fierza, Koman, Skavica and Vau i Dejës.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Two other power stations, such as the Banjë and Moglicë, are along the Devoll in the south.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It has the 10th-largest oil reserves in Europe and the 58th in the world.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country's main petroleum deposits are located around the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast and Myzeqe Plain within the Western Lowlands, where the country's largest reserve is located.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Patos-Marinza, also located within the area, is the largest onshore oil field in Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP), part of the planned Southern Gas Corridor, runs for 215 kilometres (134 miles) across Albania's territory before entering the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast approximately 17 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of Fier.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania's water resources are particularly abundant in all the regions of the country and comprise lakes, rivers, springs, and groundwater aquifers.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country's available average quantity of fresh water is estimated at 129.7 cubic metres (4,580 cubic feet) per inhabitant per year, one of the highest rates in Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to data presented by the Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP) in 2015, about 93% of the country's total population had access to improved sanitation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The freedom of press and freedom of speech, and the right to free expression are guaranteed by the Constitution of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In practice, however, media freedom has been weakened by political pressure, concentrated ownership, opaque financing, intimidation of journalists and the overlap between media, business and political interests.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania ranked 84th in the World Press Freedom Index of 2020 compiled by Reporters Without Borders.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has continued to describe the Albanian media environment as fragile, stating that press freedom and media independence are threatened by conflicts of interest between business and politics, a flawed legal framework and partisan regulation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2026, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries in the World Press Freedom Index.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH) is the public broadcaster of Albania, operating television and radio stations throughout the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The main private broadcasters include Top Channel, TV Klan, Vizion Plus, A2 CNN, Syri TV and Ora News.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian television content is also distributed in Kosovo and other Albanian-speaking territories.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that the most influential private-sector media are owned by a small number of companies with links to the political world and to highly regulated sectors such as construction.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response reported that the top four owners in the Albanian television market reach between 48.93% and 58.60% of audiences, and that the boundaries between media, politics and economics remain blurred.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to these assessments, media owners often use their outlets to protect business interests or influence governments and political parties, while state advertising and public funds are distributed in opaque ways that can create political dependence.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The media environment has become a central part of criticism of Prime Minister Edi Rama's long rule.
[src:alba/albania-p03] International media-freedom organisations and Albanian journalists have accused the government of using communication centralisation, selective access, public-relations material and attacks on critical reporters to dominate the information space.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists face political pressure, especially during elections, and that politicians limit editorial independence by politicising regulators and the public broadcaster.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response cited BIRN Albania editor Gjergj Erebara as saying that large parts of the Albanian media landscape operate under government propaganda and disinformation pressure.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or politically connected business interests face particular risks.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that journalists investigating crime and corruption are frequent targets of threats and that self-censorship is widespread.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It also reports that critical journalists are subjected to discrediting attacks by both government and opposition politicians, while organised crime remains a major threat to journalists' safety.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In March 2023, the headquarters of Top Channel was attacked with automatic weapons, killing a security guard.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The public broadcaster has also been part of the debate over media capture and political pressure.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2026, international media-freedom organisations warned that democratic reform of RTSH should not be carried out through funding cuts, suspension or closure, arguing that such measures would violate European standards for public service media.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian cinema has its roots in the 20th century and developed after the country's declaration of independence.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The first movie theater exclusively devoted to showing motion pictures was built in 1912 in Shkodër.
[src:alba/albania-p03] During the People's Republic of Albania, Albanian cinema developed rapidly with the inauguration of the Kinostudio Shqipëria e Re in Tirana.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 1953, the Albanian-Soviet epic film *The Great Warrior Skanderbeg* was released, chronicling the life and fight of the medieval Albanian hero Skanderbeg.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It went on to win an international prize at the 1954 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2003, the Tirana International Film Festival was established, the largest film festival in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Durrës Amphitheatre hosts the Durrës International Film Festival, the country's second largest film festival.
[src:alba/albania-p03] After the fall of communism in 1991, human resources in sciences and technology in Albania have drastically decreased.
[src:alba/albania-p03] As of various reports, during 1991 to 2005 approximately 50% of the professors and scientists of the universities and science institutions in the country have left Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania was ranked 67th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Telecommunication represents one of the fastest growing and dynamic sectors in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania, Telekom Albania and Albtelecom are the three large providers of mobile and internet in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] As of the Electronic and Postal Communications Authority (AKEP) in 2018, the country had approximately 2.7 million active mobile users with almost 1.8 million active broadband subscribers.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania alone served more than 931,000 mobile users, Telekom Albania had about 605,000 users and Albtelecom had more than 272,000 users.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In January 2023, Albania launched its first two satellites, *Albania 1* and *Albania 2*, into orbit, in what was regarded as a milestone effort in monitoring the country's territory and identifying illegal activities.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian-American engineer Mira Murati, the Chief Technology Officer of research organisation OpenAI, played a substantial role in the development and launch of artificial intelligence services such as ChatGPT, Codex and DALL-E.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In December 2023, Prime Minister Edi Rama announced plans for collaboration between the Albanian government and ChatGPT, facilitated by discussions with Murati.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Rama emphasised the intention to streamline the alignment of Albanian laws with the regulations of the European Union, aiming to reduce costs associated with translation and legal services.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The demographic statistics of Albania, as revealed by the 2023 census conducted by the Instituti i Statistikave (INSTAT), indicated a population of 2,402,113, with a notable decline from the 2,821,977 recorded in the 2011 census.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The decrease in inhabitants began after the disintegration of the communist regime in Albania and is associated with significant shifts within the political, economic, and social structure of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] A principal factor in this transition incorporates a decline in fertility rates coupled with an increase in emigration, both contributing to persistent demographic changes and challenges.
[src:alba/albania-p03] It is forecast that the population will continue shrinking for the next decade at least, depending on the actual rates and the level of migration.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Currently, the population density of Albania is measured at 83.6 inhabitants per square kilometer with a varied distribution of inhabitants across different regions.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The counties of Tirana and Durrës showcase substantial concentrations of people, accounting for about 41% of the overall demographic of Albania, with 32% residing in Tirana and 9% in Durrës.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Conversely, more peripheral and rural counties such as Gjirokastër and Kukës present significantly lower population densities, with each aiding 3% to the overall population.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Historically, the Albanian people have established several communities in many regions throughout Southern Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Albanian diaspora has been formed since the late Middle Ages, when they emigrated to escape either various socio-political difficulties or the Ottoman conquest of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Following the fall of communism, large numbers of Albanians have migrated to countries such as Australia, Canada, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian minorities are present in the neighbouring territories such as the west of North Macedonia, the southeast of Montenegro, Kosovo in its entirety and parts of southern Serbia.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Altogether, the number of ethnic Albanians living abroad is estimated to be higher than the total population inside Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] As much as a third of those born in the country's borders now live outside of it, making Albania one of the countries with the highest rate of outmigration relative to its population in the world.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2022 the birth rate was 20% lower than in 2021, largely due to emigration of people of childbearing age.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Subsequent to the collapse of communism in 1991, Albania has undergone a remarkable transformation in its urban landscape, emerging as one of the fastest urbanising countries in Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] At the forefront of this transformation is the Tirana–Durrës agglomeration, a densely populated urban corridor situated along the western coast of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] This corridor has become the primary locus of population growth and settlement development, attracting a significant influx of internal migrants from the country's peripheral areas.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Despite an overall decline of the country's total population, the proportion of the urban demographic has consistently progressed from 47% in 2001 to 65% in 2023.
[src:alba/albania-p03] This sustained increase, coupled with the concentration in the Tirana-Durrës region, has led to a spread of regional imbalances, with the peripheral areas, particularly Dibër and Kukës, experiencing severe depopulation.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The official language of the country is Albanian which is spoken by the vast majority of the country's population.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Its standard spoken and written form is revised and merged from the two main dialects, Gheg and Tosk, though it is notably based more on the Tosk dialect.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Shkumbin river is the rough dividing line between the two dialects.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Among minority languages, Greek is the second most-spoken language in the country, with 0.5 to 3% of the population speaking it as first language, mainly in the country's south where its speakers are concentrated.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Other languages spoken by ethnic minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Serbo-Croatian, Macedonian, Bulgarian, Gorani, and Roma.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Macedonian is official in the Pustec Municipality in East Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In the 2023 population census, 91.07% reported Albanian as the language spoken at home.
[src:alba/albania-p03] 1.54% declared to speak at home another language, 0.57% multiple languages, 1.21% gave no answer and 5.59% were unavailable.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Among young people aged 25 or less, English, German and Turkish have seen rising interest after 2000.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Italian and French have had a stable interest, while Greek has lost much of its previous interest.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The trends are linked with cultural and economic factors.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In the mid-2010s, an increasing number of Albanians showed interest in learning the German language, which has been explained as part of "a Western Balkan trend of preparing to integrate into the German labor market".
[src:alba/albania-p03] Some of them have gone to Germany for studies or work.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania and Germany have agreements for cooperating in helping young people of the two countries know both cultures better.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Due to a sharp rise in economic relations with Turkey, interest in learning Turkish, in particular among young people, was also growing on a yearly basis in the 2010s.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Designated national and cultural minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Greek, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Serb, Roma, Egyptian, Bosnian and Bulgarian peoples, as well as Gorani and Jews as other minority groups.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania is a secular and religiously diverse country with no official religion.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Freedom of religion, belief and conscience are guaranteed under the country's constitution.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania is nevertheless ranked among the least religious countries in the world.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Religion constitute an important role in the lives of only 39% of the country's population.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In another report, 56% considered themselves religious, 30% considered themselves non-religious, while 9% defined themselves as convinced atheists.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The Muslim Albanians are spread throughout the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Orthodox and Bektashis are mostly found in the south, whereas Catholics mainly live in the north.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2008, there were 694 Catholic churches and 425 Orthodox churches, 568 mosques and 70 bektashi takyas in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] During modern times, the Albanian republican, monarchic and later communist regimes followed a systematic policy of separating religion from official functions and cultural life.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country has never had an official religion either as a republic or as a kingdom.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In the 20th century, the clergy of all faiths was weakened under the monarchy and ultimately eradicated during the 1950s and 1960s, under the state policy of obliterating all organised religion from the territories of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The communist regime persecuted and suppressed religious observance and institutions and entirely banned religion.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country was then officially declared to be the world's first atheist state.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Religious freedom has returned, however, since the end of communism.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Islam survived communist era persecution and reemerged in the modern era as a practised religion in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Some smaller Christian sects in Albania include Evangelicals and several Protestant communities including Seventh-day Adventist Church, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The first recorded Protestant of Albania was Said Toptani, who travelled around Europe and returned to Tirana in 1853, where he preached Protestantism.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The first evangelical Protestants appeared in the 19th century and the Evangelical Alliance was founded in 1892.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Nowadays, it has 160 member congregations from different Protestant denominations.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Following mass emigration to Israel after the fall of communism, there are only 200 Albanian Jews left in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In Albania, education is secular, free, compulsory, and based on three levels.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The academic year is apportioned into two semesters, beginning in September or October and ending in June or July.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albanian is the primary language of instruction in the country's academic institutions.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The study of a first foreign language is mandatory and taught most often at elementary and bilingual schools.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Languages taught in schools are English, Italian, French and German.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Albania has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 98.7%, with 99.2% for men and 98.3% for women.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Compulsory primary education is divided into two levels, elementary and secondary school, from grade one to five and six to nine, respectively.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Pupils are required to attend school from the age six until they turn 16.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Upon successful completion of primary education, all pupils are entitled to attend high schools, specialising in any field, including arts, sports, languages, sciences, and technology.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Tertiary education is optional and has undergone a thorough reformation and restructuring in compliance with the principles of the Bologna Process.
[src:alba/albania-p03] There are a significant number of private and public institutions of higher education in Albania's major cities.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Tertiary education is organised into three successive levels, the bachelor, master, and doctorate.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The constitution of Albania guarantees its citizens equal, free, and universal health care.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The health care system is organised into primary, secondary, and tertiary healthcare, and is in a process of modernisation and development.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The life expectancy at birth in Albania is 77.8 years, ranking 37th in the world and surpassing several developed countries.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The average healthy life expectancy is 68.8 years, ranking 37th in the world.
[src:alba/albania-p03] The country's infant mortality rate was estimated at 12 per 1,000 live births in 2015.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2000, the country had the world's 55th-best healthcare performance, as defined by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
[src:alba/albania-p03] Cardiovascular disease is the principal cause of death in Albania, accounting for 52% of deaths.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Accidents, injuries, malignant and respiratory diseases are other primary causes of death.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Neuropsychiatric disease has also increased due to recent demographic, social, and economic changes in the country.
[src:alba/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania had a fruit and vegetable supply of 886 grams per capita per day, the fifth-highest supply in Europe.
[src:alba/albania-p03] Compared to other developed and developing countries, Albania has a relatively low rate of obesity, probably thanks to the Mediterranean diet.
[src:alba/albania-p03] According to 2016 WHO data, 21.7% of adults in the country are clinically overweight, with a Body mass index (BMI) score of 25 or more.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The red and black national colours are displayed on the flag of Albania that is adorned with a double-headed eagle as the foremost recognised national symbol of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p04] With the black eagle portraying bravery and strength, the red field symbolises the fortitude and sacrifices of the Albanian people.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The eagle is linked with the legacy of the national hero Gjergj Kastrioti, renowned as Skanderbeg, who led a prosperous resistance movement against Ottoman rule.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Rooted in the Middle Ages, it emerged as a heraldic symbol in the Principality of Arbër and among notable Albanian dynasties such as the Dukagjini, Kastrioti, Muzaka and Thopia clans.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Amid the Albanian Renaissance, marking the resurgence of Albanian national identity and aspirations for independence, the Albanian eagle regained its prominence.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Its importance reached its culmination with Albania's declaration of independence in 1912, when Ismail Qemali raised it as the national flag in Vlorë.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The coat of arms of Albania is an adaptation of the flag of Albania and the seal of Skanderbeg.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The coat comprises the black double-headed eagle positioned at the centre of a red field.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Above the eagle, it carries the helmet of Skanderbeg that is crowned with the head of a golden horned goat.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Ti Shqipëri, më jep nder, më jep emrin Shqipëtar, which translates to "You Albania, give me honour, give me the name Albanian", is the national motto of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It finds its foundation in the legacy of national poet Naim Frashëri, who held a renowned role during the Albanian Renaissance.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The national anthem of Albania, "Himni i Flamurit", was composed by Asdreni and adopted as such following Albania's independence in 1912.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian traditional clothing, with its contrasting variations for the northern Gheg and southern Tosk Albanians, is a testament to Albania's history, cultural diversity and ethnic identity.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Gheg men wear a light-colored shirt paired with wide loose-fitting trousers referred to as the Tirq.
[src:alba/albania-p04] These trousers are securely fastened by a wide woven belt, the Brez.
[src:alba/albania-p04] An integral component of their costume is the Xhamadan, a woolen red velvet vest adorned with folkloric motifs and gold patterns.
[src:alba/albania-p04] They also wear a distinctive dome-shaped hat known as the Qeleshe, crafted from wool, with its origins tracing back to the Illyrians.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Conversely, Tosk men opt for the Fustanella, a knee-length garment designated as the national costume, typically white with pleats, accompanied by a white shirt.
[src:alba/albania-p04] They also wear a beige or dark blue Xhamadan reminiscent of the Gheg attire.
[src:alba/albania-p04] To complete their attire, men wear knee-high socks referred to as Çorape and leather shoes known as Opinga.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The attire of Gheg and Tosk women is renowned for its rich palette of colors and intricate filigree detailing, displayed across various components including ear ornaments, finger rings, necklaces, belt buckles and buttons.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Key components include a long, light-toned shirt paired with an apron, often accompanied by a woolen or felt mantle referred to as the Xhoka.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Additional upper garments, such as the Dollama or Mintan, may be layered, along with a headscarf known as Kapica or Shall.
[src:alba/albania-p04] A distinctive variation incorporates a pair of aprons, including the Pështjellak at the rear and the Paranik at the front.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Integral to the traditional attire of Gheg women is the ancient Xhubleta.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Dedicated efforts have been undertaken to preserve and promote the dress, acknowledging its significance as an emblem of Albanian heritage.
[src:alba/albania-p04] As a testament to its importance, the Xhubleta has been inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The distinctive bell-shaped garment is fashioned in black and enriched with embroidered ethnic Albanian motifs, showcasing the remarkable craftsmanship of northern Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Its crafting process involves multiple intricate stages, encompassing the preparation of shajak fabric and the precise cutting techniques.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The artistic history of Albania has been particularly influenced by a multitude of ancient and medieval people, traditions and religions.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It covers a broad spectrum with mediums and disciplines that include painting, pottery, sculpture, ceramics and architecture all of them exemplifying a great variety in style and shape, in different regions and period.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The rise of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empire in the Middle Ages was accompanied by a corresponding growth in Christian and Islamic art in the lands of Albania which are apparent in examples of architecture and mosaics throughout the country.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Centuries later, the Albanian Renaissance proved crucial to the emancipation of the modern Albanian culture and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of literature and art whereas artists sought to return to the ideals of Impressionism and Romanticism.
[src:alba/albania-p04] However, Onufri, Kolë Idromeno, David Selenica, Kostandin Shpataraku and the Zografi Brothers are the most eminent representatives of Albanian art.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The architecture of Albania reflects the legacy of various civilisations tracing back to the classical antiquity.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Major cities in Albania have evolved from within the castle to include dwellings, religious and commercial structures, with constant redesigning of town squares and evolution of building techniques.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Nowadays, the cities and towns reflect a whole spectrum of various architectural styles.
[src:alba/albania-p04] In the 20th century, many historical as well as sacred buildings bearing the ancient influence were demolished during the communist era.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Ancient architecture is found throughout Albania and most visible in Byllis, Amantia, Phoenice, Apollonia, Butrint, Antigonia, Shkodër and Durrës.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Considering the long period of rule of the Byzantine Empire, they introduced castles, citadels, churches and monasteries with spectacular wealth of visible murals and frescos.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Perhaps the best known examples can be found in the southern Albanian cities and surroundings of Korçë, Berat, Voskopojë and Gjirokastër.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Involving the introduction of Ottoman architecture there was a development of mosques and other Islamic buildings, particularly seen in Berat and Gjirokastër.
[src:alba/albania-p04] A productive period of Historicism, Art Nouveau and Neoclassicism merged into the 19th century, best exemplified in Korçë.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The 20th century brought new architectural styles such as the modern Italian style, which is present in Tirana such as the Skanderbeg Square and Ministries.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It is also present in Shkodër, Vlorë, Sarandë and Durrës.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Moreover, other towns received their present-day Albania-unique appearance through various cultural or economic influences.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Socialist classicism arrived during the communist era in Albania after the Second World War.
[src:alba/albania-p04] At this period many socialist-styled complexes, wide roads and factories were constructed, while town squares were redesigned and numerous of historic and important buildings demolished.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Notable examples of that style include the Mother Teresa Square, Pyramid of Tirana, Palace of Congresses and so on.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Three Albanian archaeological sites are included in the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:alba/albania-p04] These include the ancient remains of Butrint, the medieval Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastër, and Natural and Cultural Heritage of the Ohrid region site shared with North Macedonia since 2019.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Furthermore, the royal Illyrian tombs, the remains of Apollonia, the ancient Amphitheatre of Durrës and the Fortress of Bashtovë has been included on the tentative list of Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian folk music is a prominent part of the national identity, and continues to play a major part in overall Albanian music.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Folk music can be divided into two stylistic groups, mainly the northern Gheg varieties, and southern Lab and Tosk varieties.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Northern and southern traditions are contrasted by a rugged tone from the north, and the more relaxed southern form of music.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Many songs concern events from Albanian history and culture, including traditional themes of honour, hospitality, treachery, and revenge.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The first compilation of Albanian folk music was made by two Himariot musicians, Neço Muka and Koço Çakali, in Paris, during their work with Albanian soprano Tefta Tashko-Koço.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Several gramophone compilations were recorded at the time by the three artists, which eventually led to the recognition of Albanian iso-polyphony as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Festivali i Këngës is a traditional Albanian song contest organised by the national broadcaster Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH).
[src:alba/albania-p04] The festival is celebrated annually since its inauguration in 1962 and has launched the careers of some of Albania's most successful singers including Vaçe Zela and Parashqevi Simaku.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It is significantly a music competition among Albanian performers presenting unreleased songs in premiere, composed by Albanian authors and voted by juries or by public.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Contemporary artists Rita Ora, Bebe Rexha, Era Istrefi, Dua Lipa, Ava Max, Bleona, Elvana Gjata, Ermonela Jaho, and Inva Mula have achieved international recognition for their music, while soprano Ermonela Jaho has been described by some as the "world's most acclaimed soprano".
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian opera singer Saimir Pirgu was nominated for the 2017 Grammy Award.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The cultural renaissance was first of all expressed through the development of the Albanian language in the area of church texts and publications.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The Protestant reforms invigorated hopes for the development of the local language and literary tradition, when cleric Gjon Buzuku translated the Catholic liturgy into Albanian, trying to do for Albanian what Martin Luther had done for German.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Meshari (*The Missal*) written by Gjon Buzuku was published in 1555 and is considered one of the first literary work of written Albanian during the Middle Ages.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The refined level of the language and the stabilised orthography must be the result of an earlier tradition of written Albanian, a tradition that is not well understood.
[src:alba/albania-p04] However, there is some fragmented evidence, pre-dating Buzuku, which indicates that Albanian was written from at least the 14th century.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian writings from these centuries must not have been religious texts only, but historical chronicles too.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The *History of Skanderbeg* is still the foundation of Skanderbeg studies and is considered an Albanian cultural treasure, vital to the formation of Albanian national self-consciousness.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The most famous Albanian writer in the 20th and 21st century is probably Ismail Kadare.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Throughout the centuries, Albanian cuisine has been widely influenced by Albanian culture, geography and history, and as such, different parts of the country enjoy specific regional cuisines.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Cooking traditions especially vary between the north and the south, owing to differing topography and climate that essentially contribute to the excellent growth conditions for a wide array of herbs, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanians produce and use many varieties of fruits such as lemons, oranges, figs, and most notably, olives, which are perhaps the most important element of Albanian cooking.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Spices and other herbs such as basil, lavender, mint, oregano, rosemary, and thyme are widely used, as are vegetables such as garlic, onions, peppers, potatoes, tomatoes, as well as legumes of all types.
[src:alba/albania-p04] With a coastline along the Adriatic and Ionian in the Mediterranean Sea, fish, crustaceans, and seafood are a popular and an integral part of the Albanian diet.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Otherwise, lamb is the traditional meat for different holidays and religious festivals for both Christians and Muslims, although poultry, beef, and pork are also in plentiful supply.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Tavë kosi ("soured milk casserole") is the national dish of Albania, consisting of lamb and rice baked under a thick, tart veil of yoghurt.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Fërgesë is another national dish, made up of peppers, tomatoes, and cottage cheese.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Pite is also popular, a baked pastry with a filling of a mixture of spinach and gjizë (curd) or mish (ground meat).
[src:alba/albania-p04] Petulla, a traditional fried dough, is also a popular speciality, and is served with powdered sugar or feta cheese and different sorts of fruit jams.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Flia consists of multiple crêpe-like layers brushed with cream and served with sour cream.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Krofne, similar to Berliner doughnuts, are filled with jam, or chocolate and often eaten during winter.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Coffee is an integral part of the Albanian lifestyle.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The country has more coffee houses per capita than any other country in the world.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Tea is also enjoyed both at home or outside at cafés, bars, or restaurants. Çaj Mali (Sideritis tea) is enormously beloved, and a part of the daily routine for most Albanians.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It is cultivated across Southern Albania and noted for its medicinal properties.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian wine is also common throughout the country, and has been cultivated for thousands of years.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albania has a long and ancient history of wine production, and belongs to the Old World of wine producing countries.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albania participated at the Olympic Games in 1972 for the first time.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The country made their Winter Olympic Games debut in 2006.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albania missed the next four games, two of them due to the 1980 and 1984 boycotts, but returned for the 1992 games in Barcelona.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Since then, Albania have participated in all games.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albania normally competes in events that include swimming, athletics, weightlifting, shooting and wrestling.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The country have been represented by the National Olympic Committee of Albania since 1972.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The nation has participated at the Mediterranean Games since the games of 1987 in Syria.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The Albanian athletes have won a total of 43 (8 gold, 17 silver and 18 bronze) medals from 1987 to 2013.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Popular sports in Albania include football, weightlifting, basketball, volleyball, tennis, swimming, rugby union and gymnastics.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Football is by far the most popular sport in Albania.
[src:alba/albania-p04] It is governed by the Football Association of Albania (Albanian: *Federata Shqiptare e Futbollit*, F.SH.F.), which has membership in FIFA and UEFA.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albania scored their first ever goal in a major tournament and secured their first ever win in European Championship when they beat Romania by 1–0 in a UEFA Euro 2016 match on 19 June 2016.
[src:alba/albania-p04] The most successful football clubs are Skënderbeu, KF Tirana, Dinamo Tirana, Partizani and Vllaznia.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Weightlifting is one of the most successful individual sports for the Albanians, with the national team winning medals at the European Weightlifting Championships and the rest international competitions.
[src:alba/albania-p04] Albanian weightlifters have won a total of 16 medals at the European Championships with one of them being gold, seven silver and eight bronze.
[src:alba/albania-p04] In the World Weightlifting Championships, the Albanian weightlifting team has won in 1972 a gold, in 2002 a silver, and in 2011 a bronze medal.
